irst=Giovanni|date=2017-11-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|10\n|6\n| align=\"left\"| [[Sony Masterworks]]/[[OKeh Records|OKeh]]\n|}\n\n'''As guest'''\n* [[Frank Foster (musician)|Frank Foster]] \u2013 ''[[The Loud Minority]]'' ([[Mainstream Records|Mainstream]], 1972)\n* [[Stanley Clarke]] - ''[[Children of Forever]]'' ([[Polydor Records|Polydor]], 1973)\n* [[Roy Ayers]] \u2013 ''[[Coffy (soundtrack)|Coffy]]'' (Polydor, 1973) \u2013 as Denise Bridgewater\n* [[Buddy Terry]] \u2013 ''[[Lean on Him]]'' (Mainstream, 1973)\n* [[Norman Connors]] \u2013 ''Love from the Sun'' ([[Buddah Records|Buddah]], 1974)\n* [[Cecil McBee]] \u2013 ''[[Mutima]]'' ([[Strata-East Records|Strata-East]], 1974)\n* [[Charles Sullivan (musician)|Charles Sullivan]] \u2013 ''[[Genesis (Charles Sullivan album)|Genesis]]'' (Strata-East, 1974)\n* [[Carlos Garnett]] - ''[[Black Love (Carlos Garnett album)|Black Love]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]], 1974)\n* [[Stanley Clarke]] \u2013 ''I Wanna Play for You'' ([[Nemperor Records|Nemperor]], 1979)\n* [[Hollywood Bowl Orchestra]] \u2013 ''Prelude to a Kiss - The Duke Ellington Album'' ([[Philips Records|Philips Classics]], 1996)\n* [[BWB (band)|BWB]] \u2013 ''Groovin' '' ([[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], 2002)\n* [[Christian McBride]] \u2013 ''[[Conversations with Christian]]'' ([[Mack Avenue Records|Mack Avenue]], 2011)\n\n'''Film Soundtrack'''\n*''[[La Vengeance d'une blonde|La Vengeance d'une Blonde]]'' - ''[[People and Places (song)|People And Places]]'' - Dee Dee Bridgewater & [[Philip Bailey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dee Dee Bridgewater}}\n* [http://www.deedeebridgewater.com/ Official site]\n*{{IMDb name|0108815}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n* [http://www.rockwired.com/rockwired_interviews_dee_dee_bridgewater.html Interview at Rockwired.com]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050909083732/http://www-music.duke.edu/jazz_archive/artists/bridgewater.dee.dee/01/bio.html |date=September 9, 2005 |title=Biography }}\n\n{{TonyAward MusicalFeaturedActress 1947-1975}}\n\n{{NPR}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridgewater, Dee Dee}}\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Knights of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sanremo Music Festival winners]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Michigan]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:Food and Agriculture Organization]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American jazz singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Dee Dee Bridgewater\n| image            = Dee_dee.jpg\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Denise Eileen Garrett\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1950|5|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Flint, Michigan]], U.S. \n| genre            = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Singer, actress, record producer, songwriter, UN goodwill ambassador, radio host\n| years_active     = 1966\u2013present\n| label            = DDB Records, [[Sony Masterworks]], [[OKeh Records]], [[Verve Records|Verve]], [[Elektra Records|Elektra]], [[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| website          = {{URL|deedeebridgewater.com}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Thad Jones/Mel Lewis Orchestra]], [[Horace Silver]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Sonny Rawlins]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Betty Carter]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Theo Croker]], [[China Moses]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Stanley Clark]], [[Sarah Vaughn]], [[Max Roach]], [[Rahsaan Roland Kirk]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Herbie Hancock]]\n}}\n\n'''Dee Dee Bridgewater''' (n\u00e9e '''Denise''' '''Garrett''', May 27, 1950) is an American [[jazz]] singer. She is a three-time Grammy Award-winning singer-songwriter, as well as a [[Tony Award]]-winning stage actress. For 23 years, she was the host of National Public Radio's syndicated radio show ''JazzSet with Dee Dee Bridgewater''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/event/music/353256144/jazzset-signs-off|title=JazzSet Signs Off|website=Npr.org|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> She is a [[United Nations]] Goodwill Ambassador for the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/tempref/GI/Reserved/ambassadors/finalVersion/amb/bridgewater_en.htm|title=FAO Ambassabors Programme|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn Denise Eileen Garrett in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], she was raised Catholic in [[Flint, Michigan]]. Her father, Matthew Garrett, was a jazz trumpeter and teacher at Manassas High School, and through his playing, she was exposed to jazz early on. At the age of sixteen, she was a member of a Rock and [[R&B]] trio, singing in clubs in [[Michigan]]. At 18, she studied at [[Michigan State University]] before she went to the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]. With the school's jazz band, she toured the [[Soviet Union]] in 1969.<ref name=\"NYTimes1998-09-22\">{{cite news\n | title = A Singer Is Returning to a Stage Where It All Began\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/22/arts/arts-in-america-a-singer-is-returning-to-a-stage-where-it-all-began.html\n | last =Thomas | first =Jo | authorlink= | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = September 22, 1998\n | access-date  = 2016-10-06\n}}</ref>\n\nThe next year, she met trumpeter [[Cecil Bridgewater]], and after their marriage, they moved to [[New York City]], where Cecil played in [[Horace Silver]]'s band. In the early 1970s, Bridgewater joined the [[Thad Jones/Mel Lewis Big Band|Thad Jones-Mel Lewis Jazz Orchestra]] as lead vocalist.<ref>Larkin, Colin. ''The Guinness Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', Guinness, page 547, (1995) \u2013 {{ISBN|1-56159-176-9}}</ref> This marked the beginning of her jazz career, and she performed with many of the great jazz musicians of the time, such as [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Max Roach]], [[Rahsaan Roland Kirk]] and others. She performed at the [[Monterey Jazz Festival]] in 1973. In 1974, her first solo album, entitled ''Afro Blue'', appeared, and she performed on Broadway in the [[Musical theater|musical]] ''[[The Wiz]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/production/the-wiz-majestic-theatre-vault-0000007830|title=The Wiz Broadway @ Majestic Theatre - Tickets and Discounts|website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> For her role as [[Glinda the Good Witch]] she won a [[Tony Award]] in 1975 as \"Best Featured Actress\", and the musical also won the 1976 [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Show Album]].\n\n[[File:Ddbridg014.JPG|left|thumb|In concert in 1990]]\nShe subsequently appeared in several other stage productions. After touring [[France]] in 1984 with the musical ''[[Sophisticated Ladies]]'', she moved to [[Paris]] in 1986. The same year saw her in ''Lady Day,'' as [[Billie Holiday]], for which role she was nominated for the [[Laurence Olivier Award]], as well as recording the song \"''Precious Thing\"'' with [[Ray Charles]], featured on her album ''[[Victim of Love (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Victim of Love]]''.\n\nIn the late 1980s and early 1990s, she returned from the world of Pop and [[Contemporary R&B]] to Jazz. She performed at the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in Italy and the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] in 1990, and four years later, she finally collaborated with [[Horace Silver]], whom she had long admired, and released the album ''Love and Peace: A Tribute to Horace Silver''. Performed also at the [[San Francisco Jazz Festival]] (1996). Her 1997 tribute album ''[[Dear Ella]]'' won her the 1998 [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album]], and the 1998 album ''[[Live at Yoshi's (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Live at Yoshi's]]'' was also worth a Grammy nomination. Performed again at the [[Monterey Jazz Festival]] (1998). She has also explored on ''[[This Is New (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|This Is New]]'' (2002) the songs of [[Kurt Weill]], and, on her next album ''[[J'ai Deux Amours (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|J'ai Deux Amours]]'' (2005), the French Classics.\n[[File:Hancock Bridgewater.JPG|thumb|Herbie Hancock and Dee Dee Bridgewater giving a masterclass to musicians in [[Rabat]],  [[Morocco]]]]\nHer album ''[[Red Earth (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Red Earth]]'', released in 2007, features Africa-inspired themes and contributions by numerous musicians from [[Mali]]. Performed at the [[San Francisco Jazz Festival]] (2007). On December 8, 2007 she performed with the [[Terence Blanchard]] Quintet at the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/calendar/index.cfm?fuseaction=showEvent&event=MIJPB|title=Kennedy Center: The Movie Music of Spike Lee and Terence Blanchard|website=Kennedy-center.org|accessdate=November 3, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818231324/http://www.kennedy-center.org/calendar/index.cfm?fuseaction=showEvent&event=MIJPB|archivedate=August 18, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She tours frequently, including overseas gigs around the world. October 16, 2009 found her opening the Shanghai JZ Jazz Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jzmg.net/en/review-2009|title=Review 2009 {{!}} Shanghai JZ Festival Official Website|website=www.jzmg.net|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>, in which she sang tunes associated with [[Ella Fitzgerald]], along with Ellington compositions and other jazz standards.\n\nAs a Goodwill Ambassador to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|United Nations\u2019 Food and Agriculture Organization]], Bridgewater continues to appeal for international solidarity to finance global grassroots projects in the fight against world hunger. Awarded Honorary Doctorates from [[University of Michigan\u2013Flint|University of Michigan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.umflint.edu/2012/10/23/international-jazz-star-dee-dee-bridgewater-to-receive-um-flint-honorary-degree/|title=International Jazz Performer to Receive Honorary Degree at UM-Flint Commencement|last=News|first=UM-Flint|date=2012-10-23|website=UM-Flint NOW|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> and [[Berklee College of Music]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/news/julio-iglesias-doug-morris-harvey-mason-dee-dee-bridgewater-receive-honorary-degrees|title=Julio Iglesias, Doug Morris, Harvey Mason, Dee Dee Bridgewater to Receive Honorary Degrees {{!}} Berklee College of Music|website=www.berklee.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>, Bridgewater makes a concerted effort to mentor and nurture young artists. \n\nIn April 2017, Bridgewater was the recipient of an [[NEA Jazz Masters]] Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arts.gov/honors/jazz/dee-dee-bridgewater|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater|date=2016-06-07|website=NEA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> with honors bestowed at the Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C. and in 2018 was awarded the 2018 Maria Fisher Founder's Award by the [[Thelonious Monk Institute of Jazz|Thelonious Monk/Hancock Institute of Jazz]].<ref>https://hancockinstitute.org/dee-dee-bridgewater-2018/</ref> She is currently on tour worldwide in support of her latest CD, \u201c''[[Memphis... Yes, I'm Ready|Memphis...Yes, I'm Ready]]''\u201d.\n\n==Acting==\nDee Dee had appeared in such films as the 1979 film ''[[The Fish That Saved Pittsburgh]]'' and the 1984 film ''[[The Brother from Another Planet]]''. She has made a guest appearance in the hit sitcom ''[[Benson (TV series)|Benson]]'' and the hit sci-fi fantasy TV series ''[[Highlander: The Series]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nBridgewater is the mother to three children, Tulani Bridgewater (from her marriage to [[Cecil Bridgewater]]), [[China Moses]] (from her marriage to theater, film and television director [[Gilbert Moses]]) and Gabriel Durand (from her last marriage to French concert promoter Jean-Marie Durand). Her eldest daughter, Tulani Bridgewater, attended the [[The Mirman School|Mirman School for Gifted Children]] in Los Angeles, CA. She went on to graduate from the [[\u00c9cole Internationale Bilingue- Victor Hugo School|Ecole Active Bilingue]] in Paris, France at age 16, going on to graduate from [[Vassar College]]. She serves as Bridgewater's manager under her firm Bridgewater Artists Management and runs Bridgewater's production company and record label (DDB Productions, Inc. And DDB Records). Daughter [[China Moses]] is an accomplished singer, songwriter, producer, radio host and MTV VJ (France). Her critically acclaimed albums have earned her an international reputation as heir to Bridgewater's legacy. Moses tours worldwide, occasionally sharing the bill with Bridgewater.\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n===Grammy Awards===\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]. Bridgewater has won two Grammys with eight nominations.<ref name=Grammy>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/dee-dee-bridgewater|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater|website=Grammy.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Work\n!Category\n!Label\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Live in Paris (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Live in Paris]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance, Female]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Keeping Tradition]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1995 \n| ''[[Love and Peace: A Tribute to Horace Silver]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 \n| ''[[Dear Ella]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Live at Yoshi's (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Live at Yoshi's]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[J'ai Deux Amours]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Red Earth (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Red Earth - A Malian Journey]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Eleanora Fagan (1915-1959): To Billie with Love from Dee Dee Bridgewater|Eleanora Fagan (1915\u20131959): To Billie With Love From Dee Dee]]''\n| [[Best Jazz Vocal Album]]\n| {{win}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other accolades===\n\n* First American to be inducted into the Haut Conseil de la Francophonie\n*[[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres|Commandeur dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] Award (France)\n* [[Tony Award]], Best Featured Actress in a Musical, ''[[The Wiz]]'', 1975\n*[[Laurence Olivier Award]] Nomination, 1987<ref>{{Citation|title=Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical|date=2019-04-07|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Laurence_Olivier_Award_for_Best_Actress_in_a_Musical&oldid=891415478|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n*[[AUDELCO]] Award, Outstanding Performance in a Musical-Female, ''LADY DAY'', 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.audelco.org/2014-nominees/|title=2014 Winners {{!}} Audience Development Committee, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n*[[ASCAP]] Foundation Champion Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/dee-dee-bridgewater-receive-ascap-foundation-champion-award|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater Earns Prestigious ASCAP Honor|date=2017-10-06|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>, 2017\n*Doris Duke Award, 2018<ref>https://www.ddcf.org/what-we-fund/performing-arts/goal-and-strategies/support-for-artists/unrestricted-support-for-artists/doris-duke-artist-awards/dee-dee-bridgewater</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! colspan=\"4\"|Chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Label\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"35\"| [[Billboard 200|US Pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dee-dee-bridgewater/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater: Billboard 200|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|website=billboard.com}}</ref> \n! width=\"35\"|[[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dee-dee-bridgewater/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater: Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|website=billboard.com}}</ref> \n! width=\"35\"| [[Jazz Albums|US Jazz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dee-dee-bridgewater/chart-history/jazz-albums|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater: Jazz Albums|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|website=billboard.com}}</ref> \n! width=\"35\"| [[Billboard charts#albums|US Tra. Jazz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dee-dee-bridgewater/chart-history/traditional-jazz-albums|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater: Traditional Jazz Albums|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|website=billboard.com}}</ref>  \n|-\n| 1974\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Afro Blue (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Afro Blue]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| Trio\n|-\n| 1976\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Dee Dee Bridgewater (1976 album)|Dee Dee Bridgewater]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n|-\n| 1977\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Just Family]]''\n|170\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n|-\n| 1979\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Bad for Me (album)|Bad for Me]]''\n|182\n|57\n|30<ref name=BB>{{cite work|title=Billboard's Best Selling Jazz Albums|page=66|volume=91|date=June 2, 1979|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n|-\n| 1980\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Dee Dee Bridgewater (1980 album)|Dee Dee Bridgewater]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n|-\n| 1987\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Live in Paris (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Live in Paris]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]]\n|-\n| 1989\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Victim of Love (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Victim of Love]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n|-\n| 1992\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[In Montreux]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Keeping Tradition]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n| align=\"left\"| [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Love and Peace: A Tribute to Horace Silver|Love and Peace:]]''\n''[[Love and Peace: A Tribute to Horace Silver|A Tribute to Horace Silver]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|47\n|13\n| align=\"left\"| [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n-\n|-\n| 1996\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Prelude to a Kiss: The Duke Ellington Album]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|\n|\n| align=\"left\"| [[Philips]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Dear Ella]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|5\n|12\n| align=\"left\"| [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Live at Yoshi's (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Live at Yoshi's]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|44\n|20\n| align=\"left\"| [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n|-\n| 2002\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[This Is New (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|This Is New]]'' \n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|26\n|7\n| align=\"left\"| [[Verve Records|Verve]]\n|-\n|2005\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[J'ai Deux Amours (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|J'ai Deux Amours]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|37\n|16\n| align=\"left\"| DDB Records\n|-\n|2007\n| align=\"left\"| [[Red Earth (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|''Red Earth: A Malian Journey'']]\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|31\n|16\n| align=\"left\"| DDB Records\n|-\n| 2010\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Eleanora Fagan (1915-1959): To Billie with Love from Dee Dee Bridgewater|Eleanora Fagan (1915-1959):]]''\n''[[Eleanora Fagan (1915-1959): To Billie with Love from Dee Dee Bridgewater|To Billie with Love from Dee Dee Bridgewater]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|19\n|14\n| align=\"left\"| [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]]\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| 2011\n|''[[Midnight Sun (Dee Dee Bridgewater album)|Midnight Sun]]'' (Compilation)\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|20\n|9\n| align=\"left\"| [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Dee Dee's Feathers]]''\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|11\n|6\n| align=\"left\"| [[Sony Masterworks]]/[[OKeh Records|OKeh]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Memphis... Yes, I'm Ready]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/23/arts/music/dee-dee-bridgewater-memphis-yes-im-ready.html|title=Dee Dee Bridgewater Throws Herself a Memphis Soul Party|last=Russonello|first=Giovanni|date=2017-11-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|10\n|6\n| align=\"left\"| [[Sony Masterworks]]/[[OKeh Records|OKeh]]\n|}\n\n'''As guest'''\n* [[Frank Foster (musician)|Frank Foster]] \u2013 ''[[The Loud Minority]]'' ([[Mainstream Records|Mainstream]], 1972)\n* [[Stanley Clarke]] - ''[[Children of Forever]]'' ([[Polydor Records|Polydor]], 1973)\n* [[Roy Ayers]] \u2013 ''[[Coffy (soundtrack)|Coffy]]'' (Polydor, 1973) \u2013 as Denise Bridgewater\n* [[Buddy Terry]] \u2013 ''[[Lean on Him]]'' (Mainstream, 1973)\n* [[Norman Connors]] \u2013 ''Love from the Sun'' ([[Buddah Records|Buddah]], 1974)\n* [[Cecil McBee]] \u2013 ''[[Mutima]]'' ([[Strata-East Records|Strata-East]], 1974)\n* [[Charles Sullivan (musician)|Charles Sullivan]] \u2013 ''[[Genesis (Charles Sullivan album)|Genesis]]'' (Strata-East, 1974)\n* [[Carlos Garnett]] - ''[[Black Love (Carlos Garnett album)|Black Love]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]], 1974)\n* [[Stanley Clarke]] \u2013 ''I Wanna Play for You'' ([[Nemperor Records|Nemperor]], 1979)\n* [[Hollywood Bowl Orchestra]] \u2013 ''Prelude to a Kiss - The Duke Ellington Album'' ([[Philips Records|Philips Classics]], 1996)\n* [[BWB (band)|BWB]] \u2013 ''Groovin' '' ([[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], 2002)\n* [[Christian McBride]] \u2013 ''[[Conversations with Christian]]'' ([[Mack Avenue Records|Mack Avenue]], 2011)\n\n'''Film Soundtrack'''\n*''[[La Vengeance d'une blonde|La Vengeance d'une Blonde]]'' - ''[[People and Places (song)|People And Places]]'' - Dee Dee Bridgewater & [[Philip Bailey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dee Dee Bridgewater}}\n* [http://www.deedeebridgewater.com/ Official site]\n*{{IMDb name|0108815}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n* [http://www.rockwired.com/rockwired_interviews_dee_dee_bridgewater.html Interview at Rockwired.com]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050909083732/http://www-music.duke.edu/jazz_archive/artists/bridgewater.dee.dee/01/bio.html |date=September 9, 2005 |title=Biography }}\n\n{{TonyAward MusicalFeaturedActress 1947-1975}}\n\n{{NPR}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridgewater, Dee Dee}}\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Flint, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Knights of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sanremo Music Festival winners]]\n[[Ca