{"title_page": "The Archers", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the radio series}}\n{{short description|British radio soap opera}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox radio show\n| show_name = The Archers\n| image = TheArchersLogo.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n| other_names =\n| format = Soap opera\n| runtime = 12 minutes (formerly 15 minutes)\n| country = United Kingdom\n\n| home_station = [[BBC Light Programme]]<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\"/><br />later [[BBC Home Service]]<br />now [[BBC Radio 4]]\n| syndicates =\n| television =\n| starring =\n| creator = [[Godfrey Baseley]]\n| writer =\n| director =\n| producer = Julie Beckett\n| editor = [[Jeremy Howe (radio drama editor)|Jeremy Howe]]<ref name=\"Howe-starts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/entries/553a51d0-ff7f-4c7a-9fac-0bf00204c238| title= Jeremy Howe's first day as the new editor of The Archers | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | publisher= BBC| date= 23 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| executive_producer =\n| narrated =\n| record_location = [[BBC Birmingham]]\n| first_aired = 29 May \n| last_aired = 2 June 1950 (Pilot)<br /> 1 January 1951\u2013present\n| num_series =\n| num_episodes = 19,207 (as of 16 April 2020)<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/the-archers/about | title= About The Archers | accessdate=6 January 2008 | date=31 December 2010| publisher= BBC }}</ref><br />Six per week, plus 75 mins. omnibus\n| audio_format = Stereophonic sound\n| opentheme = [[Barwick Green]] [[File:Barwick Green.ogg]]\n| endtheme =\n| website = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers Archers homepage]\n| podcast = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr/episodes/downloads.rss The Archers podcast]\n}}\n\n'''''The Archers''''' is a British radio soap opera on [[BBC Radio 4]]{{mdash}}the [[BBC]]'s main spoken-word [[radio channel|channel]]{{mdash}}broadcast since 1951. It was initially billed ''an everyday story of country folk'' and now, ''a contemporary drama in a rural setting''.<ref name=\"shryaneobit\">{{cite news | first = Jack | last = Adrian | title = Tony Shryane Obituary ||url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/tony-shryane-37242.html| newspaper = [[The Independent on Sunday]] | date = 9 October 2003 | accessdate = 10 July 2018 | location = London }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=History of the BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0168wd7|publisher=BBC|date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Having aired over 19,100 episodes, it is the world's longest-running drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/60-things-you-never-knew-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-archers-2173365.html|title=60 things you never knew you wanted to know about The Archers|date=1 January 2011|website=The Independent|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8226200/Archers-no-longer-educates-farmers.html|title=Archers 'no longer educates farmers'|first=Neil|last=Midgley|date=27 December 2010|accessdate=9 January 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nFive pilot episodes were aired in 1950 and the first episode was broadcast nationally on 1 January 1951. A significant show in [[British popular culture]], and with over five million listeners, it is Radio 4's most listened-to non-news programme,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/12_december/30/archers.shtml | title= The Archers clocks up 55 years | accessdate=6 January 2008| date=30 December 2005| publisher= BBC Press Office }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Neil | last=Midgley | title= The Archers hold record ratings | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7926999/The-Archers-scores-record-ratings-of-over-5m-listeners.html | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=5 August 2010| location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Ultimate Reference Guide to British Popular Culture|url=https://www.oxford-royale.co.uk/articles/the-ultimate-reference-guide-to-british-popular-culture.html|agency=Oxford Royale|date=23 November 2016}}</ref> and with over one million listeners via the internet, the programme holds the record for [[BBC Radio]] [[Online and offline|online]] listening figures.<ref>{{cite news | first = Nicole | last=Martin | title = The Archers online dwarfs Chris Moyles | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/08/17/nradio217.xml | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph| date = 20 August 2007| accessdate =6 January 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, a panel of 46 broadcasting industry experts, of which 42 had a professional connection to the BBC, listed ''The Archers'' as the second-greatest radio programme of all time.<ref name=\"Desert Island Discs\">{{cite web | title= Desert Island Discs 'greatest radio show of all time'|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47204636| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 12 February 2019| publisher= [[BBC News]] | accessdate= 1 March 2019 }}</ref> Partly established with the aim towards educating farmers following [[World War II]], ''The Archers'' soon became a popular source of entertainment for the population at large, attracting nine million listeners by 1953.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''The Archers'' is set in the fictional village of Ambridge in the fictional county of [[Borsetshire]], in England. Borsetshire is situated between what are, in reality, the contiguous counties of [[Worcestershire]] and [[Warwickshire]], south of Birmingham in [[The Midlands]]. Ambridge is possibly based on the village of [[Elmbridge, Worcestershire|Cutnall Green]],<ref name=Cutnall>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8455995/Have-they-found-the-real-Ambridge.html |title=Have they found the real Ambridge? |last1=Wynne-Jones |first1=Jonathan |last2=Howie |first2=Michael |date=17 April 2011 |website=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Newspapers |access-date=26 February 2018 }}</ref> though various other villages claim to be the inspiration for Ambridge; ''The Bull'', Ambridge's [[pub]], is modelled on The Old Bull in [[Inkberrow]],<ref>Compare Ambridge's [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/gallery_60s_timeline.shtml?select=05 The Bull] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628165347/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/gallery_60s_timeline.shtml?select=05 |date=28 June 2008 }} with Inkberrow's [http://www.inkberrow.org.uk/ The Old Bull].</ref> whereas [[Hanbury, Worcestershire|Hanbury]]'s St Mary the Virgin is often used as a stand-in for Ambridge's [[parish church]], St Stephen's.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/news/anyquestions_transcripts_20060922.shtml | title= Transcript: Any Questions? 22 September 2006 | accessdate=6 January 2008| date=22 September 2006 | publisher= [[BBC Radio 4]] }}</ref><ref>Compare Ambridge's [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/ed_emma_will_gallery.shtml?select=10 St Stephen's] with Hanbury's [http://www.hevac-heritage.org/items_of_interest/heating/churches_&_chapels/hanbury_church/hanbury_church.htm St Mary the Virgin].</ref>\n\nOther fictional villages include Penny Hassett, Loxley Barrett,<ref>[http://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/schools/201540/loxley-barrett-primary-school Loxley Barrett Primary School]; goodschoolsguide.co.uk</ref> Darrington, Hollerton, Edgeley, Waterley Cross and Lakey Green. The [[county town]] of Borsetshire is [[Borchester]], and the nearest big city is the [[cathedral city]] of [[Borsetshire|Felpersham]]. Felpersham also has a university. Anywhere further from Ambridge may be referred to humorously with comments such as 'that's on the other side of Felpersham!', but characters do occasionally venture further: several attended the [[Countryside Alliance]] march in London,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2002-09-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20020922&day=0 }}</ref> there have been references to the gay scene in Manchester's [[Canal Street (Manchester)|Canal Street]]. There have been scenes set in other places in the United Kingdom and abroad, with some characters residing overseas such as in South Africa and Hungary.\n\nSince [[Easter Sunday]] 1998, there have been six episodes a week, from Sunday to Friday, broadcast at around 19:03 following the news summary. All except the Friday evening episode are repeated the following day at 14:02. The six episodes are re-run unabridged in the Sunday morning [[omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] at 10:00. On [[Remembrance Sunday]], the Omnibus edition begins at the earlier time of 09:15. This information is available in the press and on the BBC's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 The Archers |publisher=BBC |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|3|27}}, due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] restrictions, weekly programming reduces to five episodes. Friday's episode will cease to be broadcast. The Sunday omnibus will be correspondingly reduced in length to one hour.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Archers characters}}\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Archer family|Archers]]'s [[family farm]], Brookfield, combines arable, dairy, beef, and sheep. It is a typical example of [[mixed farming]] which has been passed down the generations from Dan, the original farmer, to his son Phil and is now co-owned by Phil and Jill's four children: David, who manages it with his wife Ruth; Shula Hebden-Lloyd, owner of the riding stables, was married to  Alistair, a vet; her twin Kenton, runs the village's only pub with his wife Jolene; and the widowed Elizabeth Pargeter. Jill lives in Brookfield with her son David, his wife Ruth and their children Pip, Josh, and Ben.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Aldridge family|Aldridges]] at [[Home farm (agriculture)|Home Farm]]. Brian, who is portrayed as a money-driven [[agribusiness]]man and his wife Jennifer. They have five children: the two Jennifer brought into their marriage: Adam, a farmer married to chef Ian Craig and Debbie a farmer based in Hungary; two born into the marriage, Kate with a family abandoned in South Africa, and Alice married to farrier Chris Carter; and schoolboy Ruairi, Brian's son by one of his affairs. The family also includes Kate's daughter Phoebe and Jennifer's sister Lilian.\n* The Bridge Farm [[List of The Archers characters#The Archer family|Archers]] practise [[organic farming]]. Their operations include a farm shop, a farm caf\u00e9, a [[vegetable box scheme]] and a dairy. Tony and Pat's children are Helen and Tom, and their three grandchildren: Johnny, who is the son of their dead son John; and Henry and Jack.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Pargetter family|Pargetters]], a [[landed gentry]] family who have to make their [[stately home]], Lower Loxley Hall, pay the bills as a public attraction. The family includes Nigel Pargetter's widow, Elizabeth {{n\u00e9e}} Archer, her son Freddie and his twin sister Lily.\n* The [[Joe Grundy|Grundys]], formerly struggling [[tenant farmer]]s who were brought to prominence in the late 1970s and early 1980s as comic characters, but are now seen as doggedly battling adversity.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Carter family|Carters]], Neil and Susan. Their son, Chris, is married to Alice Aldridge; their daughter, Emma, has successively married brothers, Will and Edward Grundy.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#Lynda Snell|Snells]], Lynda, married to the long-suffering Robert, is the butt of many jokes, although her sheer energy makes her a stalwart of village life.\n\n==Ambridge==\n{{See also|List of fictional towns and villages}}\n* ''Arkwright Hall'' is a large Victorian mansion with a 17th-century atmosphere. The building served as a community centre for many years, containing a soundproofed room and field studies centre. Later it fell into disrepair, but was renovated when Jack Woolley leased the mansion to the [[Landmark Trust]]; architect Lewis Carmichael led the restoration of the building to its [[Victorian era|Victorian]] splendour.\n* ''Bridge Farm'' is a {{Convert|168|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm previously on Berrow Estate, but now owned by Pat and Tony Archer. The farm became wholly dedicated to [[organic farming]] in 1984, in a storyline inspired by a scriptwriter's visit to Brynllys farm in [[Ceredigion]], the home of [[Rachel's Organic]].<ref name=Times6847838>{{cite news | title=The Soil Association | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article6847838.ece | work=The Times | location=London | date=25 September 2009| accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> In 2003, Tom Archer began producing his Bridge Farm pork sausages. In early 2013, the family decided to sell their dairy herd and buy organic milk instead and the following year, Tony Archer bought a small [[Angus cattle|Aberdeen Angus]] herd.\n* ''Brookfield Farm'' is a {{Convert|469|acre|ha|adj=on}} mixed farm which was managed by Dan Archer and then by his son Phil. After Phil's retirement in 2001, his son David Archer took over.\n* ''Grange Farm'' was a working farm run by the Grundys until their eviction in 2000. The farmhouse, along with {{Convert|50|acre|ha|}} of land, was sold to Oliver Sterling, who then began \"hobby farming\". He took young Ed Grundy on as cow man and later gave him full responsibility for running the farm.\n* ''Grey Gables'', once a country club, is now a luxurious hotel. The late Caroline Sterling bought it with her husband Oliver Sterling. The hotel boasts a pool, spa, health club and a golf course. Ian Craig is the executive chef.\n* ''Home Farm'' is a {{Convert|1922|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm, by far the largest in Ambridge. In recent years, Home Farm expanded into soft fruit and deer farming.\n* ''Lower Loxley Hall'' is a large 300-year-old country house located just outside Ambridge. It serves primarily as a conference centre. \n* ''The Bull'', the village's only [[Public house|pub]], is perhaps the most recognisable structure in Ambridge\n* ''St. Stephen's Church'', established in 1281, dates back to [[Normans|Norman]] times. The church has undergone many changes over the years, including a number of different vicars. The eight bells are rung by a group led by Neil Carter.\n* Ambridge still has a ''[[Village shop#United Kingdom|village shop and post office]]'', originally thanks to Jack Woolley's philanthropy. The business is now a community shop managed by Susan and run by a team of volunteers.\n* ''Willow Farm'' is owned by the Tucker family. After Betty's death in 2005, the house was divided to accommodate Roy and his family. The [[Agricultural land|farmland]] is home to Neil Carter's pigs.\n\n==Topicality==\nUnlike some soap operas, episodes of ''The Archers'' portray events taking place on the date of broadcast, allowing many topical subjects to be included. Real-life events which can be readily predicted in advance are often written into the script, such as the annual [[Oxford Farming Conference]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/oxford_conference.shtml | title= Oxford Farming Conference | accessdate= 17 February 2008 | publisher= BBC Radio 4 | date= 3 January 2008 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080628092518/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/oxford_conference.shtml | archivedate= 28 June 2008 }}</ref> and the [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-06-27}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20060625&day=2 }}</ref> On some occasions, scenes recorded at these events are planned and edited into episodes shortly before transmission.\n\nMore challengingly for the production team, some significant but unforeseen events require scenes to be rewritten and rerecorded at short notice, such as the death of [[Princess Margaret]] (particularly poignant because she had appeared as herself on the programme),<ref name=\"princess margaret\">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/princess_margaret.shtml | title= Princess Margaret Remembered | accessdate=17 February 2008| date=10 February 2002 | publisher= BBC Radio 4}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2002-02-10}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20020210&day=0 }}</ref> the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|World Trade Center attacks]],<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-09-12}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010909&day=3 }}</ref> and the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2005-07-11}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20050710&day=1 }}</ref> The events and implications of the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth crisis|2001 foot-and-mouth crisis]] required many \"topical inserts\"<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010218&day=4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-23}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010218&day=5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-27}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010225&day=2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-03-01}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010225&day=4 }}</ref> and the rewriting of several storylines.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/drama_in_a_crisis.shtml | title= Drama in a Crisis | accessdate=17 February 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4| date=2 March 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Oliver Sterling, owner of Grange Farm, together with his tenant, Ed Grundy, elected to vaccinate the badgers on their farm in an attempt to prevent the spread of bovine [[tuberculosis]]. The plotline came within weeks of the government confirming a [[Badger culling in the United Kingdom|badger cull trial]].<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01b1g9d/The_Archers_25_01_2012/ | title= The Archers 2012-01-25 | accessdate=2 February 2012| publisher=BBC Radio 4 | date=25 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on 29 March 2020 that the programme would include reference to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]] from 4 May onwards.<ref name=\"bbc-29mar20\">{{cite web |title=Changes to The Archers during Coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/coronavirus-archers |website=www.bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Actors==\nUnlike television soaps, ''The Archers'' actors are not held on retainers and work on the series usually for a few days a month. By the nature of the storylines concentrating on particular groups of characters, in any one week out of a cast of about 60, the episodes include approximately 20{{ndash}}30 speaking-characters. Most of the cast do acting work on other projects and can disappear for long periods if they are working on commitments such as films or television series. [[Tamsin Greig]] plays Debbie Aldridge and has appeared on many television series such as ''[[Green Wing]]'', ''[[Love Soup]]'', ''[[Black Books]]'' and ''[[Episodes (TV series)|Episodes]]'', so Debbie manages a farm in [[Hungary]] and her visits to Ambridge are infrequent. [[Felicity Jones]] played Emma Carter from the age of 15 but after a period of studying at [[Wadham College, Oxford]], she gave up the role to move into television and cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-hottest-star-in-hollywood-ndash-who-owes-it-all-to-ambridge-2199000.html|title=The hottest star in Hollywood \u2013 who owes it all to Ambridge|accessdate=10 July 2018|date=31 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome of the actors, when not playing their characters, earn their money through different jobs altogether: Charlotte Connor, when not playing Susan Carter (credited as Charlotte Martin), works full-time as a senior research psychologist at the Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health Foundation; her office is a short walk from [[BBC Birmingham]], and thus she is able to fit her work around recordings.<ref>David Brindle [https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/feb/09/young-people-mental-health-problems-log-on?INTCMP=SRCH \"Young people log on for shared headspace\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 February 2011</ref> Meanwhile, Graham Blockey, who plays Robert Snell, worked till recently as a full-time [[general practitioner]] in Surrey, commuting to and from [[BBC Birmingham]] at weekends and on his days off. He kept his role secret from his patients, for fear of losing their respect, until his retirement from medicine in March 2017.<ref>Matthew Weaver [https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/31/surrey-gp-reveals-archers-character-robert-snell-graham-blockey \"GP reveals his 30-year secret life as Archers character Robert Snell\"], ''The Guardian'', 31 March 2017</ref> Other examples include Felicity Finch (Ruth Archer), who also works as a BBC journalist having travelled on a number of occasions to Afghanistan; and Ian Pepperell (Roy Tucker), who manages a pub in the [[New Forest]].<ref>Chris Arnot, [https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/oct/06/60-years-archers-10-things-new \"The Archers at 60\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 October 2010.</ref>\n\n==History==\nA five-episodes pilot series started on [[Whit Monday]], 29 May 1950, and continued throughout that week.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5xGwGj4NgfGRJ1B2mFqg6QM/frequently-asked-questions | title= Frequently Asked Questions | work = The Archers| accessdate=16 June 2019| publisher= BBC Radio 4}}</ref> It was created by [[Godfrey Baseley]] and was broadcast to the English Midlands in the Regional Home Service, as 'a farming [[Dick Barton]]'. Recordings were sent to London, and the BBC decided to commission the series for a longer national run. In the five pilots the Archers owned Wimberton Farm, rather than Brookfield. Baseley subsequently edited ''The Archers'' for 22 years.\n\nSince 1 January 1951, five 15-minute episodes (since 1998, six 12\u00bd-minute episodes) have been transmitted each week, at first on the [[BBC Light Programme]]<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\">Donovan, Paul (1991), ''The Radio Companion''. London: Grafton; p. 8.</ref> and subsequently on the [[BBC Home Service]] (now [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]). Early afternoon repeats of the previous evening's episode began on 14 December 1964. The original scriptwriters were Geoffrey Webb and [[Edward J. Mason]], who were also working on the nightly thriller series about the special agent Dick Barton. The popularity of his adventures partly inspired ''The Archers'', which eventually took over Barton's evening slot. At first, however, the national launch placed the serial at the 'terrible'<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; p.24. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> time of 11.45&nbsp;am, but it moved to Dick Barton's former slot of 6.45&nbsp;pm from Monday, 2 April 1951. An omnibus edition of the week's episodes began on Saturday, 5 January 1952.\n\nOriginally produced with collaborative input from the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]], ''The Archers'' was conceived as a means of disseminating information to farmers and smallholders to help increase productivity in the [[Postwar]] era of [[Rationing in the United Kingdom|rationing]] and food shortages.<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\"/>\n\n''The Archers'' originally centred on the lives of three farmers; Dan Archer, farming efficiently with little cash, Walter Gabriel, farming inefficiently with little cash, and George Fairbrother, a wealthy businessman farming at a loss for tax purposes (which one could do in those days).<ref>Norman Painting, ''Forever Ambridge'' (1975)</ref> The programme was hugely successful, winning the National Radio Awards' 'Most entertaining programme of the Year' award jointly with ''[[Take It from Here]]'' in 1954, and winning the award outright in 1955, in which year the audience was reported to have peaked at 20 million.<ref name=\"The Listener 29 August 1985\">''The Listener'', 29 August 1985.</ref>\n\nAt the late 1950s, despite the growth of television and radio's consequent decline, the programme was still claiming eleven million listeners and was also being transmitted in Canada, Australia, and New Zealand.<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; pp. 75\u201376. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> By the mid-1970s, however, the audience for the two daily broadcasts and the weekend omnibus combined was less than 3 million<ref>Smethurst (1996) ''The Archers'', p. 144.</ref> and in 1976 the BBC Radio Four Review Board twice considered whether or not the programme should be axed.<ref>Hendy, David (2007), ''Life On Air, A history of Radio Four'' Oxford University Press, p. 205. {{ISBN|978-0-19-924881-0}}</ref> The serial's woes at this time were seen to mirror the poor standing of radio drama in general, described as \"a failure to fully shake off the conventions of non-realism which had prevailed in the 1940s and 1950s.\"<ref>Hendy, David (2007) ''Life On Air'', p. 204.</ref>\n\nProgramme chief Jock Gallagher, responsible for ''The Archers'', described these as the serial's \"dog days\".<ref>Hendy (2007), p. 204.</ref> Sweeping editorial reforms followed, included the introduction of women writers (there had been none before 1975), two of whom, Helen Leadbeater and Margaret Phelan, were credited with giving the programme a new definitive style of writing and content, although some listeners complained about their radical feminism.<ref>Glenys Roberts, ''London Evening Standard'', London; 17 March 1983.</ref>\n\nIn 1980 [[Julie Burchill]] commented that the women of Ambridge were no longer stuck with \"the gallons of greengage jam old-guard male scriptwriters kept them occupied with for over twenty years\"; but were 'into post-natal depression and alcoholism on the way to self-discovery'.<ref>Hendy (2007), p, 207.</ref> By the mid-1980s the Radio Four Review Board noted that scripts, directing and acting was \"very good\" and sometimes \"better than ever\".<ref>Hendy (2007), p. 208.</ref> In August 1985 ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'' said that the programme's revival was \"sustained by some of the best acting, direction and writing on radio.\"<ref name=\"The Listener 29 August 1985\"/>\n\n[[Tony Shryane]] MBE was the programme's producer from 1 January 1951 to 19 January 1979. Vanessa Whitburn was the programme's editor from 1992 till 2013. Whitburn took service leave from March to July 2012, when [[John Yorke (producer)|John Yorke]], a former executive producer of ''[[EastEnders]]'', was the acting editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2012/02/acting_archers_editor.html|title=BBC \u2013 The Archers Blog: Acting Archers editor|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> Yorke's arrival prompted charges that the programme was importing the values of ''EastEnders'' to Borsetshire, with fans and commentators complaining that characters were behaving unrealistically simply to generate conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/ourcomments/view/335079|title=EastEnders formula is failing in Ambridge|author=Simon Edge|work=Daily Express|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> This was denied by Yorke, who wrote that he agreed to take over \"on one condition \u2013 that it stayed exactly as it was and that I didn't have to change anything.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2012/06/is_the_archers_going_to_get_da.html|title=BBC \u2013 The Archers Blog: Is The Archers going to get 'darker and bigger? No.|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nVanessa Whitburn was succeeded as editor by [[Sean O'Connor (producer)|Sean O'Connor]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/leisure/showbiz/10593342.O_Connor_takes_Archers__top_job/|title=O'Connor takes Archers' top job|author=Press Association 2014|work=The Argus|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> In September 2016, [[Huw Kennair-Jones]] took over as editor though O'Connor continued to oversee the Helen and Rob storyline until its conclusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5vFGJHJDWPdPSY77RrmtyQD/meet-the-archers-new-editor-huw-kennair-jones| title= Meet The Archers' new editor, Huw Kennair-Jones | accessdate = 18 September 2016 | publisher= BBC}}</ref> Kennair-Jones announced in October 2017 that he was to leave the BBC to work as commissioning editor for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/entries/cab07c63-5403-42be-b16c-9c74875ee062| title= Huw Kennair-Jones steps down as editor of The Archers | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | publisher= BBC| date= 4 October 2017 }}</ref> The short presence of two successive Archers editors in the job led to concerns that there might be a trend of radio drama editing being seen as \"training ground\" for higher-paid positions in TV.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/10/11/archers-will-trouble-editors-keep-poached-tv-star-says/|title= Archers will be in trouble if editors keep being poached by TV, star says |date=11 October 2017|accessdate=9 September 2018|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last1= Furness |first1= Hannah }}</ref> [[Alison Hindell]], the BBC's head of Audio Drama until October 2018, took over as acting editor before<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/sep/13/the-archers-helen-titchner-huw-kennair-jones-bbc-radio-4|title= The Archers: former Sky executive takes over show as Helen Titchener plot ends |date=13 September 2016|accessdate=9 September 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last1= Jackson |first1= Jasper }}</ref> and after<ref name=\"Hindell-Howe\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/hindell-succeed-howe-r4-commissioning-editor-drama-and-fiction-814556|title= Hindell becomes Radio 4 commissioning editor for Drama and fiction |date=19 June 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018|magazine=[[The Bookseller]]}}</ref> Kennair-Jones's time in charge. She effectively swapped with Jeremy Howe when she succeeded him as the BBC's commissioning editor for drama and fiction<ref name=\"Hindell-Howe\" /> and he started as editor of the Archers in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite press release | date = 7 February 2018 | title = Jeremy Howe announced as new editor of The Archers |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/jeremy-howe-archers | publisher = [[BBC]] | access-date= 25 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Howe-starts\"/>\n\nSince 2007, ''The Archers'' has been available as a [[podcast]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr/episodes/downloads |title= Podcasts |work = The Archers | accessdate=10 February 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref>\n\n===Death of Grace Archer===\nOne of the most controversial ''Archers'' episodes was broadcast on 22 September 1955, which coincided with the launch of the UK's first commercial television station. Phil and Grace Archer had been married just a few months earlier, and their blossoming relationship was the talk of the nation. However, searching for a story which would demonstrate some real tragedy among the increasingly unconvincing episode cliff-hangers, Godfrey Baseley had decided that Grace would have to die. The scripts for the week commencing 19 September 1955 were written, recorded, and broadcast on each day, with an \"exercise in topicality\" given as the explanation to the cast. On Thursday, listeners heard the [[sound effect]]s of Grace trying to rescue ''Midnight'', her horse, from a fire in the stable at Brookfield and the crash of a falling [[Beam (structure)|timber beam]].<ref name=\"ep10000\">{{cite episode|title= {{date|1989-05-26}}|number= 10,000|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 }}</ref>\n\nWhether the timing of the episode was a deliberate attempt to overshadow the opening night of the BBC's first commercial rival has been debated ever since. It was certainly planned some months in advance, but it may well be that the actual date of the death was changed during the scriptwriting stage to coincide with [[History of ITV|the launch of Associated-Rediffusion]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Smethurst |title = The Archers| year = 1996 |publisher= |location= | isbn = | page = 63 |chapter = Dead Girls Tell No Tales |quote = Even this presupposes that the BBC realized the impact that the 'death' would have&nbsp;\u2014 and all the evidence is that the BBC was totally taken by surprise.}}</ref> Deliberate or not, the episode attracted widespread media attention, being reported by newspapers around the world.\n\nThis controversy has been parodied twice: in \"[[The Bowmans (Hancock)|The Bowmans]]\", an episode of the television comedy programme ''Hancock'', and in the play ''[[The Killing of Sister George]]'' and [[The Killing of Sister George (film)|its 1968 film adaptation]]. On the 50th anniversary of ITV's launch, [[Ysanne Churchman]], who played Grace, sent them a congratulatory card signed \"Grace Archer\".\n\nIn 1996, William Smethurst recounted a conversation with Baseley in which he reveals his real motivation for killing off Grace Archer: Churchman was encouraging the other actors to join a trade union.<ref>{{cite book |author=Smethurst |title = The Archers |year = 1996 |publisher = |location = |isbn =|page = 64 |chapter = Dead Girls Tell No Tales |quote='She was trying to get the actors to join a trade union,' he told the author of this book, in 1995, 'so I killed her off. Very few of the original actors were professionals. I'd taken them on because they were countrymen with natural country voices. But she was stirring them up and trying to get them to join the actors' union, and saying we should only employ union actors, which would have been fatal.'}}</ref>\n\n===Longevity===\nThe actor [[Norman Painting]] played Phil Archer continuously from the first trial series in 1950 until his death on 29 October 2009. His last ''Archers'' performance was recorded just two days before his death, and was broadcast on 22 November.<ref name=\"bbc-obituary\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8331558.stm|title=Voice of Phil Archer dies aged 85|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> He is cited in ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the longest-serving actor in a single soap opera.<ref name=\"bbc-obituary\"/> Under the pseudonym \"Bruno Milna\", Painting also wrote around 1,200 complete episodes, which culminated in the 10,000th episode.\n\nJune Spencer has played Peggy Archer/Woolley from the pilot episode onwards,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/radio4/junespencer.shtml |title=Biographies: June Spencer OBE, The Archers |accessdate=1 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106073640/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/radio4/junespencer.shtml |archivedate=6 January 2009 }}</ref> though not for all of the period since. According to ''Who's Who in The Archers 2008'',<ref>{{cite book | last = Davies | first = Keri | title = Who's Who in ''The Archers'', 2008 | publisher = [[BBC Books]] | year = 2007 | location = [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] | page = 4 | isbn = 978-1-84607-326-7}}</ref> episode 15,360 was to be broadcast on 1 January 2008.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2008-01-01}}|number= 15,360|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20071230&day=2 }}</ref> Episode 15,000 was broadcast on 7 November 2006.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-11-07}}|number= 15,000|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20061105&day=2 }}</ref>\n\n===Sixtieth anniversary===\nThe Archers reached its 60th anniversary on 1 January 2011 and to mark this achievement, a special half-hour episode was broadcast on Sunday, 2 January, on BBC Radio 4 from 7pm. The episode had been advertised as containing events that would \"shake Ambridge to the core\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/05_may/27/sopps.shtml |title=BBC Statement of Programme Policy for 2010/2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> This phrase even gave rise to the [[initialism]] #SATTC trending on the website Twitter during that weekend as listeners speculated about what might happen, and then reported their views as the story unfolded.\n\nThe main events in the episode were Helen Archer giving birth to her son Henry and Nigel Pargetter falling to his death from the roof of Lower Loxley Hall. This unlikely event provoked interest in the frequency and causes of death in the series. In fact, although the incidence of accidental death and suicide is seven times the national average, the overall mortality rate in Ambridge is almost exactly what would be expected.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d7518 |pmid=22174323 |lay-url=https://www.bmj.com/press-releases/2011/12/15/series-unfortunate-events-morbidity-and-mortality-borsetshire-village |laysource=BMJ |laydate=15 December 2011 |title=A series of unfortunate events? Morbidity and mortality in a Borsetshire village |journal=BMJ |volume=343 |pages=d7518 |year=2011 |last1=Stepney |first1=R. }}</ref>\n\nThe writing out of the character of Nigel caused much controversy among listeners,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2011/01/nigel_pargetter_-_share_your_m.html | title=Nigel Pargetter \u2013 share your memories|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2011/01/the_archers_editor_on_the_60th.html | title=The Archers editor on the 60th anniversary|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> with a large number of complaints variously expressing dismay at the death of a popular character, concerns over the manner of the dismissal of the actor, belief that the promise to \"shake Ambridge to the core\" had been over-hyped, criticism of the credibility of the script and acting for the anniversary episode, and a perceived unwillingness of the editorial team to engage with these listener complaints.\n \n===Coronavirus===\nThe series initially made no mention of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]]: \" Whereas topical subjects ... have previously been added to scripts, that has not been possible with Coronavirus.\"<ref name=bbc-29mar20 /> It was announced that there would be only five broadcasts a week from 27 March \u2013 the Friday broadcast omitted \u2013 and that enough recordings were in hand until the end of April.<ref name=\"turner\">{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Camilla |title=The Archers becomes latest victim of coronavirus as Coronation Street and Emmerdale to stop filming |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/22/archers-becomes-latest-victim-coronavirus-coronation-street/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> From 4 May, the programmes will have been recorded in the actors' homes and will include references to the pandemic with \"fewer characters who will be sharing more of their private thoughts with the listener\". The series editor Jeremy Howe said, \"Coronavirus will be reflected in ''The Archers'' from May ... in a way that the programme's many loyal listeners might expect.\"<ref name=\"BBC-29mar20\">{{cite web |title=Changes to The Archers during Coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/coronavirus-archers |website=www.bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe programme has tackled many serious, contemporary social issues: rural [[drug addiction]]; rape, including [[Marital rape|rape in marriage]]; inter-racial relationships; [[direct action]] against [[Genetically modified food|genetically modified]] crops and badger culling; family break-ups; and [[civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships]], and a family being threatened by a gang of farm thieves. There has been criticism from conservative commentators, such as [[Peter Hitchens]] in 1999<ref>Peter Hitchens (2000) [1999], ''[[The Abolition of Britain]]'', pp. 262\u201364, Quartet (revised edition)</ref> that the series has become a vehicle for liberal and left-wing values and agendas, with characters behaving out of character to achieve those goals. However, one of the show's charms is to make much out of everyday, small concerns, such as the possible closure of the village shop, the loss and rediscovery of a pair of spectacles,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2005-06-07}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20050605&day=2 }}</ref> competitive [[marmalade]]-making, or nonsense such as a '[[spile]] [[wikt:trosh|troshing]]' competition,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2000-08-11}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 }}</ref> rather than the large-scale and improbable events that form the plots of many soap operas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mahoney|first=Elisabeth|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/apr/16/radio.tvandradioarts|title=Radio review: The Archers|work=The Guardian|date=16 April 2008|accessdate=16 April 2008 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9445689/Archers-loses-400000-listeners-amid-controversy-over-sexed-up-storylines.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Archers loses 400,000 listeners amid controversy over sexed-up storylines |date=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some of the actors, and confirmed in the writings of Godfrey Baseley, in its early days the show was used as a conduit for educational announcements from the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture]], one actor reading an announcement almost verbatim to another. Direct involvement of the government ended in 1972.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Salute to The Archers|journal=Agriculture: The Journal of the Ministry of Agriculture|volume=79|year=1972|page=43}}</ref> The show has reacted within a day to agricultural emergencies such as outbreaks of [[foot and mouth disease]] which affect farmers nationwide when livestock movements are restricted.\n\n==Cameo appearances==\nMany famous people have made [[cameo appearance]]s on the programme:\n* [[Princess Margaret]] and the [[Gerald Grosvenor, 6th Duke of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]] appeared in 1984 in connection with a fashion show to commemorate the centenary of the [[NSPCC]].<ref name=\"princess margaret\"/>\n* Dame [[Judi Dench]] made an appearance as the (hitherto usually silent) Pru Forrest in 1989 for the 10,000th episode. [[Terry Wogan]] was featured and [[Esther Rantzen]] was responsible for the [[sound effect]]s.<ref name=\"ep10000\"/>\n* Radio presenter [[John Peel]] appeared as himself in 1991.<ref>{{cite news | title = Peel's life away from music | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3956119.stm | publisher=BBC News|date =26 October 2004|accessdate =5 January 2008}}</ref>\n* Gardener [[Alan Titchmarsh]] judged Ambridge's entries in the [[National Gardens Scheme]] open gardens competition in May 2003.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2003-05-26}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20030525&day=1 }}</ref>\n* Radio presenter [[Chris Moyles]] appeared in June 2004 as a random customer\u2014and suspected [[National Pub of the Year]] judge\u2014in The Bull.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/moyles_visit.shtml |title= Chris Moyles braves The Bull |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |date= 10 June 2004 |publisher= BBC Radio 4 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060314092916/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/moyles_visit.shtml |archivedate= 14 March 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2004-06-14}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20040613&day=1 }}</ref>\n* Comedian [[Griff Rhys Jones]] appeared as himself in July 2004, when he was drafted into Lynda's campaign to restore the Cat and Fiddle pub.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2004-07-14}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20040711&day=3 }}</ref>\n* [[Zandra Rhodes]] played herself in an episode in September 2006 in connection with a charity fashion show.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thearchers.co.uk/archers/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=119&ItemID=2442&tabIndex=0 |title= Introducing Ms Zandra Rhodes |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |date= 11 September 2006 |publisher= Archers Addicts |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071203075126/http://www.thearchers.co.uk/archers/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=119&ItemID=2442&tabIndex=0 |archivedate= 3 December 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-09-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20060917&day=5 }}</ref>\n* [[Robert Winston]] appeared as a [[fertility]] specialist consulted by Hayley and Roy Tucker in January<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-01-02}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20061231&day=2 }}</ref> and February 2007.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-02-07}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20070204&day=3 }}</ref>\n* [[Mike Gatting]] appeared in September 2007 at the centre of a misunderstanding between Sid and Jolene Perks during the [[npower (UK)|npower]] Village Cup final at [[Lord's Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/09_september/07/archers.shtml |title= From The Ashes to The Archers |accessdate=5 January 2008|date=7 September 2007|publisher= BBC Press Office }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-09-09}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20070909&day=0 }}</ref>\n* Crime novelist [[Colin Dexter]] made a cameo in 2010.<ref>Andrew French, [http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/8301866.Morse_author_meets_the_Archers/ \"Morse author meets the Archers\"], ''Oxford Mail'', 30 July 2010.</ref>\n* [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] appeared on 16 February 2011 in connection with the [[National Osteoporosis Society]]'s 25th anniversary as well as the show's 60th anniversary.\n* In 2011, a recording of the show ''[[Gardeners' Question Time]]'' was followed by a special recording session in which Archers characters, notably Brian Aldridge, took part asking questions of the regular panellists while sitting with the audience.\n* [[Sir Bradley Wiggins]] appeared in an April 2014 episode, presenting prizes at the Ambridge [[Sport Relief]] Rough and Tumble event Challenge.\n* [[Kirstie Allsopp]] appeared in July 2014 to open the village fete.\n* In August 2014, the [[Pet Shop Boys]] were last-minute headliners at the music festival Loxfest.\n* [[Anneka Rice]] has appeared twice in Ambridge; in March 1993 and in March 2016.\n* In September 2016, in an hour-long episode concluding a highly publicised storyline in which Helen Titchener had stabbed her abusive husband Rob, some notable names guest starred as jury members, including [[Eileen Atkins]], [[Catherine Tate]] and [[Nigel Havers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37319113 |title=The Archers: Famous names on jury for Helen Titchener's trial|publisher=BBC News |date= 9 September 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Others who have made appearances include [[Britt Ekland]], [[Humphrey Lyttelton]] (1956), [[Dame Edna Everage]] and [[Antony Gormley]] (2009).\n\n==Theme tune==\nThe [[theme tune]] of ''The Archers'' is called \"[[Barwick Green]]\" and is a [[maypole dance]] from the suite ''My Native Heath'', written in 1924 by the Yorkshire composer [[Arthur Wood (composer)|Arthur Wood]]. The Sunday [[Omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] broadcast of ''The Archers'' starts with a more [[Pastoral|rustic]], [[accordion]]-arranged rendition by [[The Yetties]].<ref>{{cite book|last=The Yetties|title=Upmarket|year=1997|id=Decca SKL 5282|nopp=true|page=Track 1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/60-things-you-never-knew-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-archers-2173365.html|title=60 things you never knew you wanted to know about The Archers|last=Gonsalves|first=Rebecca|date=1 January 2011|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref> The theme for [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]]'s ''The Archers'' spinoff, ''[[Ambridge Extra]]'', is a version arranged by [[Bellowhead]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2011/apr/05/tv-theme-tunes|title=TV theme tunes: don't mess with the best|last=Heritage|first=Stuart|date=5 April 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[library music]] recording of Barwick Green was used for the pilot and during the early years of the national version, because a bid by Godfrey Baseley to have a special theme composed had been turned down on the grounds of cost, put at \u00a3250-\u00a3300.<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; p.20. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> However, once the serial had become undeniably established, a new recording of Barwick Green was authorised and performed by the BBC Midland Light Orchestra on 24 March 1954.<ref>BBC Gramophone Library</ref> This mono recording was also accompanied by four movements entitled \"A Village Suite\", composed by Kenneth Pakeman to complement Barwick Green. Excerpts from these movements were then used for a time as bridging music between scenes. The 1954 recordings were never made available to the public and their use was restricted even inside the BBC, partly because of an agreement with the Musicians' Union.\n\nIn 1992, the theme was re-recorded in stereo, retaining the previous arrangements. The venue was Symphony Hall in Birmingham, the conductor Ron Goodwin, producer David Welsby and the sound mixer Norman McLeod. The slightly different sound mixing and more leisurely tempo reportedly led some listeners to consider the new version inferior, specifically that it lacked \"brio\", although the BBC publicised the fact that the orchestra contained some of the musicians who had played in the previous recording, including Harold Rich (piano) and Norman Parker (percussion). {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n[[Robert Robinson (broadcaster)|Robert Robinson]] once compared the tune to \"the genteel abandon of a lifelong teetotaller who has suddenly taken to drink\". {{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} On [[April Fool's Day]] 2004 both ''[[The Independent]]'' and ''[[The Today Programme]]'' claimed that BBC executives had commissioned composer [[Brian Eno]] to record an electronic version of \"Barwick Green\" as a replacement for the current theme,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tumti-tumti-tumti-tum-kerrang-ambridge-in-uproar-over-enos-newwave-theme-tune-568412.html |title= Tum-ti tum-ti tum-ti tum... kerrang. Ambridge in uproar over Eno's 'new-wave' theme tune |accessdate=17 February 2008 |date=1 April 2004 | newspaper=[[The Independent]]| location=London | first=David | last=Lister}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/today/reports/arts/archers_20040401.shtml | title= New Archers Theme Tune |accessdate=17 February 2008| date=1 April 2004 | publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref> while comedian [[Billy Connolly]] included in his act the joke that the theme was so typically British that it should be the [[national anthem of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9nnnM-__JQ|title=Billy Connelly : National Anthem|last=Max Kellar|date=1 March 2008|accessdate=10 July 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, comedian [[Rainer Hersch]] conducted the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]] in a performance of the theme, live from the [[Royal Festival Hall]] to a listening [[BBC Radio 3]] audience in an attempt to confuse them. He then went on to show how similar it is to \"[[Montagues and Capulets]]\" \u2013 \"Dance of the Knights\" \u2013 from ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' by [[Sergei Prokofiev]], claiming that this was a result of Russian spies going through the BBC's rubbish bins looking for the scripts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HCVPgrQTHO0|title=Funny! 'The Archers' and 'Dance of the Knights'|via=YouTube|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Serious events===\nAt times, a cliffhanger involving the death of a major character or a disaster was marked by the traditional closing theme being replaced by the final dramatic section of ''[[Barwick Green]]'' involving trombones, cymbals and the closing bars of the signature tune \u2013 known as the \"doom music\" to some fan groups.<ref>[https://ambridgereporter.org.uk/nicknames.html See 'doom music' in 'Archers phrases']</ref> This tradition has been dropped more recently, with events such as the death of Nigel Pargetter being followed by the normal closing music despite the gravity of the incident. This has irritated some followers, who consider the jollity of the normal segment inappropriate in such circumstances.<ref>[http://www.lowfield.co.uk/archers/rip.html Seek 'doom music' in this]</ref>\n\nA brief extract from ''[[The Dream of Gerontius]]'' was played following the death of Phil Archer. When John Archer died no music was played.\n\nThere was a nod to ''The Archers'' in [[2012 Summer Olympics opening ceremony#Frankie and June say...thanks Tim .2821:52.E2.80.9322:09.29|the opening ceremony of the Olympic Games]] in London on 27 July 2012, where the theme tune was played at the beginning of a segment celebrating British culture: the sound of a radio could be heard being tuned in as ''Barwick Green'' was played.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/jul/28/olympic-games-opening-ceremony-british | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Marina | last=Hyde | title=Olympic Games opening ceremony: irreverent and idiosyncratic | date=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Casting ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Actor\n! Character\n! Duration\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[June Spencer]]\n| [[Peggy Woolley]]\n| 1950\u20131953, 1961\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lesley Saweard\n| [[Christine Barford]]\n| 1953\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Patricia Greene]]\n| [[Jill Archer]]\n| 1957\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Angela Piper\n|[[Jennifer Aldridge]]\n|1963\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Judy Bennett]]\n|[[Shula Hebden-Lloyd]]\n|1971\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Brian Hewlett\n|[[Neil Carter (The Archers)|Neil Carter]]\n|1973\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patricia Gallimore\n|[[Pat Archer]]\n|1974\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Terry Molloy]]\n|[[Mike Tucker (The Archers)|Mike Tucker]]\n|1974\u20131977, 1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Charles Collingwood (actor)|Charles Collingwood]]\n|Brian Aldridge\n|1975\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Hedli Niklaus\n|Kathy Perks\n|1977, 1978\u20131981, 1983\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Trevor Harrison\n|Eddie Grundy\n|1979\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Heather Bell\n|Clarrie Grundy\n|1979\u20131988, 2013\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Timothy Bentinck\n|David Archer\n|1982\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Charlotte Martin\n|Susan Carter\n|1983\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alison Dowling\n|Elizabeth Pargetter\n|1984\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Edward Kelsey]]\n|Joe Grundy\n|1985\u20132019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Carole Boyd]]\n|Lynda Snell\n|1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Graham Blockey\n|Robert Snell\n|1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Felicity Finch]]\n|[[Ruth Archer]]\n|1987\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Philip Molloy\n|Will Grundy\n|1989\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Tamsin Greig]]\n|Debbie Aldridge\n|1991\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[William Gaminara]]\n|Richard Locke\n|1992\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Souad Faress\n|Usha Franks\n|1994\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ian Pepperell\n|Roy Tucker\n|1995\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Buffy Davis\n|Jolene Archer\n|1996\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Jamila Massey|Jamilla Massey]]\n|Aunty Satya Khanna\n|1996\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Robin Pirongs\n|[[Sam Batton]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eric Allan]]\n|Bert Fry\n|1997\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Kim Durham\n|Matt Crawford\n|1997\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Michael Lumsden\n|Alistair Lloyd\n|1998\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Annabelle Dowler]]\n|Kirsty Miller\n|1999\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Louiza Patikas]]\n|Helen Titchener\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Richard Attlee\n|Kenton Archer\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Barry Farrimond\n|Ed Grundy\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Robert Lister\n|Lewis Charmichael\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Joanna Van Kampen\n|Fallon Rogers\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Michael Cochrane]]\n|Oliver Sterling\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sunny Ormonde\n|Lillian Bellamy\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ryan Kelly\n|Jack McCreary\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Hollie Chapman]]\n|Alice Carter\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Andrew Wincott\n|Adam Macy\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |John Telfer\n|Rev Alan Franks\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Stephen Kennedy]]\n|Ian Craig\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mona Hammond\n|Mabel Thompson\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lorraine Coady\n|Hayley Tucker\n|2006\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[John Rowe (actor)|John Rowe]]\n|Prof Jim Lloyd\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Julia Hills]]\n|Annabelle Schrivener\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Arthur Hughes\n|Ruairi Donovan\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Helen Longworth]]\n|Hannah Riley\n|2008\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Emerald O'Hanrahan]]\n|Emma Carter\n|2009\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lucy Morris\n|Phoebe Aldridge\n|2010\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[David Hargreaves (actor)|David Hargreaves]]\n|Alf Grundy\n|2012\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |James Cartwright\n|Harrison Burns\n|2013\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Daisy Badger\n|Pip Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Angus Imrie]]\n|Josh Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |David Troughton\n|Tony Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Simon Williams\n|Justin Elliott\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Tom Gibbons\n|Johnny Phillips\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |William Troughton\n|Tom Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Eleanor Bron\n|Carol Tregorran\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Perdita Avery\n|Kate Madikane\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Toby Laurence\n|Freddie Pargetter\n|2016\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Isobel Middleton\n|Anna Tregorran\n|2016\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Katie Redford\n|Lily Pargetter\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Will Howard\n|Dan Hebden-Lloyd\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Andy Hockley\n|Philip Moss\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Wilf Scolding\n|Christopher Carter\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Norris\n|Ben Archer\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mogali Masuku\n|Noluthando Madikane\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ania Sowinski\n|Lexi Viktorova\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Mali Harries]]\n|Natasha Archer\n|2018\u2013\n|}\n\n==''Ambridge Extra''==\n[[BBC Radio 4 Extra]] ran an occasional short supplement, ''[[Ambridge Extra]]'', between 2011 and 2013, featuring characters away from the Ambridge environs. Series 1 and 2 had 26 episodes and series 3, 4 and 5 had 20. The reason offered for non-renewal was limited resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/posts/Ambridge-Extra-on-Radio-4-Extra|title=BBC \u2013 Blogs \u2013 The Archers \u2013 Ambridge Extra on Radio 4 Extra|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Fan clubs==\nTwo organisations dedicated to the programme were established in the 1990s. Archers Addicts was the official body, run by members of the cast. The club had five thousand members<ref>Clive Aslet, et al [http://www.countrylife.co.uk/property/article/453925/Why-we-love-The-Archers.html \"Why we love The Archers\"], ''Country Life'', 7 May 2010.</ref> and an online shop where Archers memorabilia was sold under licence. It closed as a club on 31 December 2013 but still has a Facebook page and Twitter feed. Archers Anarchists was formed some time later, objecting to the \"castist\" assumptions propagated by the BBC, and claiming that the characters are real.\n\nThe [[usenet]] [[newsgroup]] uk.media.radio.archers<ref>[https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/uk.media.radio.archers uk.media.radio.archers on Google Groups]</ref> (referred to as UMRA by its users, who call themselves umrats) has been running since 1995. Its users include experts on subjects covered by the programme, such as the many aspects of farming, the running of small businesses, [[Campanology|bell ringing]]; lengthy discussions ensue \u2013 as well as light-hearted matters, and plot speculation. Various gatherings occur where umrats come together. The first were a series of about ten annual barbecues.<ref>[http://www.leverton.org/blosxom/Usenet/Umra/Umra%20Barbeque%202000/ UMRA 2000 barbecue]</ref> The first was attended by [[Carole Boyd]] ([[Lynda Snell]])]. They have included participants from Europe and the Americas. It has nicknames for many of the main Archers characters, such as S'aint for Shula. There are nicknames for most of the regular participants).<ref>[https://ambridgereporter.org.uk/nicknames.html UMRA nicknames and related matters]</ref> Due perhaps to it being initially more accessible in academia, the discussions can be quite detailed, though UMRA considers itself to be a friendly and welcoming group, where in particular [[flamewars]] and the like are not welcome. Despite the general decline of usenet<ref>discussion on the decline of usenet[[Usenet#Decline]]</ref> with the advent of trendier media such as Facebook and Twitter, UMRA remains a very active newsgroup compared to many. Its one-time T-shirts<ref>[http://www.clothandclay.co.uk/umra/bbq2002/bbq0208.htm UMRA T-shirt, 2002]</ref> and mugs bore the legend (in yellow on \"Barwick Green\", of course) \"An everyday story of internet folk.\"<ref>[http://www.clothandclay.co.uk/umra/index.htm UMRA logo]</ref>\n\nThe Academic Archers, founded in 2016, is a community of fans who share an academic approach to the programme. It organises an annual conference at which papers are presented which draw on academic expertise along with enjoyment. Papers from these have been published as ''The Archers in Fact and Fiction: Academic Analyses of Life in Rural Borsetshire'' (2016, Peter Lang:{{ISBN|9781787071193}}), ''Custard, Culverts and Cake'' (2017, Emerald: {{ISBN|9781787432864}} and ''Gender, Sex and Gossip: Women in The Archers'' (2019, Emerald: {{ISBN|9781787699489}} ) The group aims to be \"curious, generous and joyful\".<ref name=academic>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=Academic Archers|url=http://www.academicarchers.net|access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=rosefield>{{cite news|work=New Statesman|last=Rosefield|first=Hannah|URL=https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2016/03/what-we-learned-first-academic-archers-conference|title=What we learned from the first academic Archers conference|date=28 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=tickle>{{cite news|work=The Guardian|last=Tickle|first=Louise|URL= https://amp-theguardian-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/amp.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/13/archers-conference-ticket-radio-4-ambridge?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Feducation%2F2018%2Ffeb%2F13%2Farchers-conference-ticket-radio-4-ambridge |title=The Archers academic conference: hot ticket for Radio 4 fans and insurgency experts|date=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Parallels==\nIn 1994, the [[BBC World Service]] in Afghanistan began broadcasting ''Naway Kor, Naway Jwand'' (\"New Home, New Life\"), an everyday story of country folk incorporating pieces of useful information. Although the useful information was more likely to concern unexploded [[land mine]]s and [[opium]] addiction than the latest modern farming techniques, the inspiration and model of ''Naway Kor, Naway Jwand'' was ''The Archers'', and the initial workshopping with Afghan writers included an ''Archers'' scriptwriter.<ref>{{cite news | authorlink = Emma Brockes | first = Emma | last= Brockes | title = A long way from Ambridge | url = https://www.theguardian.com/waronterror/story/0,1361,579231,00.html | work =The Guardian | date =23 October 2001 |accessdate =16 February 2008| location=London}}</ref> A 1997 study found that listeners to the soap opera were significantly less likely to be injured by a mine than non-listeners.<ref>Neil Andersson, Charles Whitaker, Aparna Swaminathan. [http://www.ciet.org/en/documents/projects_library_docs/200652984313.pdf ''Afghanistan: The 1997 National Mine Awareness Evaluation''], [http://www.ciet.org/en/ CIET international] 1998. [http://www.ciet.org/en/documents/projects_library_docs/2006522121941.pdf \"Executive summary\"]. Retrieved 17 November 2006.</ref>\n\nIn [[Rwanda]], the BBC World Service's [[Rwanda-Rundi]] service has been broadcasting the Archers-inspired soap opera ''Urunana'' (\"Hand in Hand\") since 1999.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.developments.org.uk/articles/health-soap-opera/ | title= Country life | accessdate= 16 February 2008 | first= Josephine Irene | last= Uwamariya | author2= Kalisa Narcisse | work= Developments | publisher= [[Department for International Development]] | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080113182253/http://www.developments.org.uk/articles/health-soap-opera/ | archivedate= 13 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.comminit.com/en/node/118365 | title= Urunana Radio Soap&nbsp;\u2014 Rwanda | accessdate= 16 February 2008 | date= 14 August 2003 | publisher= The Communication Initiative Network | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110119174446/http://comminit.com/en/node/118365 | archivedate= 19 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''The Archers'' was the model for the Russian radio soap opera ''Dom 7, Podyezd 4'' (\"House 7, Entrance 4\"),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tve.org/sisters/Domsyem.html |title= Dom Syem, Podjezd Chetirie |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |first= Joan |last= Connolly |date= 22 October 2005 |publisher= [[Television Trust for the Environment]] |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071022202735/http://www.tve.org/sisters/Domsyem.html |archivedate= 22 October 2007 }}</ref> on which the former [[UK Prime Minister]], [[Tony Blair]], once made a cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.brandrepublic.com/login/News/97015/ | title= Broadcast: Tune in to the power of the viewing public |accessdate=5 January 2008| first= Jemimah |last=Bailey |date=17 October 1997 | work= Brand Republic }}</ref>\n\n==Parodies==\n[[Tony Hancock]] starred in the Galton and Simpson spoof \"[[The Bowmans]]\" in an episode of [[BBC Television]]'s ''[[Hancock's Half Hour]]''.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3_X6Y4q3vwQ \"The Bowmans\"], ''Hancock's Half Hour''</ref>\n\n[[Ned Sherrin]] produced a short 1973 film called ''The Cobblers of Umbridge''. The cast included [[Joan Sims]], [[Lance Percival]], [[Roy Kinnear]], [[Derek Griffiths]] and [[John Fortune]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069893/|title=The Cobblers of Umbridge (TV Movie 1973)|date=28 December 1973|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[John Finnemore (writer)|John Finnemore's Souvenir Programme]]'' has parodied ''The Archers'' with its recurring \"The Archers Accidentally\" sketches;<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.is/20140530205122/http://www.bbc-now.co.uk/programmes/p01pgzx0 | title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 John Finnemore's Souvenir Programme, Series 1, Episode \u2026| date=30 May 2014}}</ref> the sketches claim to portray ''The Archers'' the way it sounds to people who only listen to the show inadvertently.\n\nThe radio series of ''[[Dead Ringers (comedy)|Dead Ringers]]'' has frequently parodied characters from ''The Archers'', including a special edition.\n\nThe subtitle was parodied by [[Bill Tidy]] in his long-running cartoon of ''[[The Cloggies]]'', \"an Everyday Saga in the Life of Clog Dancing Folk\", which ran in the satirical magazine ''[[Private Eye]]'', and later in ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]''.\n\n==Books and audiobooks==\n\n===Reference works===\n* ''Forever Ambridge&nbsp;\u2014 25 Years of The Archers'' (1975) by [[Norman Painting]] ASIN B0012UT8XM\n* ''The Book of The Archers'' (1994) by [[Patricia Greene]], [[Charles Collingwood (actor)|Charles Collingwood]] and Hedli Niklaus {{ISBN|0-7181-3849-X}}\n* ''The Archers: The True Story'' (1996) by William Smethurst {{ISBN|1-85833-620-1}}\n* ''The Archers Encyclopaedia'' (2001) by Joanna Toye and Adrian Flynn {{ISBN|0-563-53718-3}}, published to coincide with the 50th anniversary of ''The Archers''\n* ''Who's Who in The Archers 2008'' by [[Keri Davies]]. {{ISBN|1-84607-326-X}}\n* ''Who's Who in The Archers 2011'' by Graham Harvey. {{ISBN|978-1-849-90015-7}}\n* ''The Archers Miscellany'' (2010) by Joanna Toye. {{ISBN|978-1-84607-754-8}}\n* ''The Road to Ambridge'' (2010) by [[June Spencer]]. {{ISBN|978-1-907532-25-2}}\n* ''The Archers Archives'' (2010) by Simon Frith & Chris Arnot. {{ISBN|978-1-84990-013-3}}\n* ''Borsetshire Life'' (2011). The county magazine. {{ISBN|978-1-902685-14-4}} see [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308063938/http://www.silkpress.co.uk/borsetshire-life.html borsetshire-life]\n\n===Novelisations===\n* ''The Archers'' by Jock Gallagher\n* ''Ambridge Summer'' by [[Keith Miles]] (1975). {{ISBN|0-85523-065-7}}\n** ''The Archers: To The Victor The Spoils'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20599-7}}\n** ''The Archers: Return to Ambridge'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20606-3}}\n** ''The Archers: Borchester Echoes'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20607-1}}\n** ''The Archers: Omnibus Edition'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-36001-1}}\n* ''The Ambridge Chronicles'' by Joanna Toye\n** ''The Archers 1951\u20131967: Family Ties'' (1998). {{ISBN|0-563-38397-6}}\n** ''The Archers 1968\u20131986: Looking For Love'' (1999). {{ISBN|0-563-55125-9}}\n** ''The Archers 1987\u20132000: Back to the Land'' (2000). {{ISBN|0-563-53701-9}}\n** ''The Archers 1951\u20131967: Family Ties'' (1998, audiobook, narrated by [[Miriam Margolyes]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55714-1}}\n** ''The Archers 1968\u20131986: Looking For Love'' (1999, audiobook, narrated by [[Stella Gonet]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55813-X}}\n** ''The Archers 1987\u20132000: Back to the Land'' (2000, audiobook, narrated by [[Stephanie Cole]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55818-0}}\n* In 1975, Tandem published a prequel novel about Ambridge in the early 1900s\n** ''Spring at Brookfield'' by [[Brian Hayles]] (1975). {{ISBN|978-0-426-16520-0}}\n\n===Published audio episodes===\n* ''Vintage Archers''\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 1'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-22586-6}}\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 2'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-22704-4}}\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 3'' (1998). {{ISBN|0-563-55740-0}} (contains several \"lost episodes\" which have been digitally restored)\n** ''The Archers: The Wedding'' Jack and Peggy tie the knot\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volumes 1\u20133'' (2001). {{ISBN|0-563-38281-3}}\n* ''Ambridge Affairs''\n** ''Ambridge Affairs: Love Triangles'' (2007). {{ISBN|1-4056-7733-3}}\n** ''Ambridge Affairs: Heartache at Home Farm'' (2007). {{ISBN|1-4056-8785-1}}\n\n===Maps===\nIn addition to books and audiobooks, purported maps of Ambridge and Borsetshire have been published.<ref>{{cite book | last = Humphreys | first = John | title = Archers Addicts Official Map of Ambridge | date = 23 September 1994 | publisher = Old House Books | isbn = 978-1-873590-08-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/wallpaper/ | title= Wallpaper |work =The Archers | accessdate=6 January 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nAn episode of ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'', broadcast on [[BBC Four]] on 1 January 2007, focused on ''The Archers''. It was narrated by [[Stephen Fry]] and included interviews with current actors and scriptwriters.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/documentaries/features/archers.shtml | title= Arena: The Archers | accessdate= 5 January 2006 | first= Emily | last= Kennedy | year= 2006 | work= BBC Four | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070117231218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/documentaries/features/archers.shtml | archivedate= 17 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of longest-serving soap opera actors]]\n* [[List of radio soaps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Sanderson, Ian (1998) ''The Archers Anarchists' A \u2013 Z''. London: Boxtree {{ISBN|0-7522-2442-5}} (the author founded the Archers Anarchists in 1995)\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers}}\n\n{{Soap operas in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n{{BBC Radio 4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archers, The}}\n[[Category:British radio soap operas]]\n[[Category:1951 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:BBC Birmingham productions]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 4 programmes]]\n[[Category:The Archers| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the radio series}}\n{{short description|British radio soap opera}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox radio show\n| show_name = The Archers\n| image = TheArchersLogo.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n| other_names =\n| format = Soap opera\n| runtime = 12 minutes (formerly 15 minutes)\n| country = United Kingdom\n\n| home_station = [[BBC Light Programme]]<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\"/><br />later [[BBC Home Service]]<br />now [[BBC Radio 4]]\n| syndicates =\n| television =\n| starring =\n| creator = [[Godfrey Baseley]]\n| writer =\n| director =\n| producer = Julie Beckett\n| editor = [[Jeremy Howe (radio drama editor)|Jeremy Howe]]<ref name=\"Howe-starts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/entries/553a51d0-ff7f-4c7a-9fac-0bf00204c238| title= Jeremy Howe's first day as the new editor of The Archers | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | publisher= BBC| date= 23 August 2018 }}</ref>\n| executive_producer =\n| narrated =\n| record_location = [[BBC Birmingham]]\n| first_aired = 29 May \n| last_aired = 2 June 1950 (Pilot)<br /> 1 January 1951\u2013present\n| num_series =\n| num_episodes = 19,202 (as of 09 April 2020)<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/the-archers/about | title= About The Archers | accessdate=6 January 2008 | date=31 December 2010| publisher= BBC }}</ref><br />Six per week, plus 75 mins. omnibus\n| audio_format = Stereophonic sound\n| opentheme = [[Barwick Green]] [[File:Barwick Green.ogg]]\n| endtheme =\n| website = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers Archers homepage]\n| podcast = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr/episodes/downloads.rss The Archers podcast]\n}}\n\n'''''The Archers''''' is a British radio soap opera on [[BBC Radio 4]]{{mdash}}the [[BBC]]'s main spoken-word [[radio channel|channel]]{{mdash}}broadcast since 1951. It was initially billed ''an everyday story of country folk'' and now, ''a contemporary drama in a rural setting''.<ref name=\"shryaneobit\">{{cite news | first = Jack | last = Adrian | title = Tony Shryane Obituary ||url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/tony-shryane-37242.html| newspaper = [[The Independent on Sunday]] | date = 9 October 2003 | accessdate = 10 July 2018 | location = London }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=History of the BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0168wd7|publisher=BBC|date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Having aired over 19,100 episodes, it is the world's longest-running drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/60-things-you-never-knew-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-archers-2173365.html|title=60 things you never knew you wanted to know about The Archers|date=1 January 2011|website=The Independent|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8226200/Archers-no-longer-educates-farmers.html|title=Archers 'no longer educates farmers'|first=Neil|last=Midgley|date=27 December 2010|accessdate=9 January 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nFive pilot episodes were aired in 1950 and the first episode was broadcast nationally on 1 January 1951. A significant show in [[British popular culture]], and with over five million listeners, it is Radio 4's most listened-to non-news programme,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/12_december/30/archers.shtml | title= The Archers clocks up 55 years | accessdate=6 January 2008| date=30 December 2005| publisher= BBC Press Office }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Neil | last=Midgley | title= The Archers hold record ratings | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7926999/The-Archers-scores-record-ratings-of-over-5m-listeners.html | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=5 August 2010| location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Ultimate Reference Guide to British Popular Culture|url=https://www.oxford-royale.co.uk/articles/the-ultimate-reference-guide-to-british-popular-culture.html|agency=Oxford Royale|date=23 November 2016}}</ref> and with over one million listeners via the internet, the programme holds the record for [[BBC Radio]] [[Online and offline|online]] listening figures.<ref>{{cite news | first = Nicole | last=Martin | title = The Archers online dwarfs Chris Moyles | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/08/17/nradio217.xml | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph| date = 20 August 2007| accessdate =6 January 2007 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, a panel of 46 broadcasting industry experts, of which 42 had a professional connection to the BBC, listed ''The Archers'' as the second-greatest radio programme of all time.<ref name=\"Desert Island Discs\">{{cite web | title= Desert Island Discs 'greatest radio show of all time'|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47204636| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 12 February 2019| publisher= [[BBC News]] | accessdate= 1 March 2019 }}</ref> Partly established with the aim towards educating farmers following [[World War II]], ''The Archers'' soon became a popular source of entertainment for the population at large, attracting nine million listeners by 1953.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''The Archers'' is set in the fictional village of Ambridge in the fictional county of [[Borsetshire]], in England. Borsetshire is situated between what are, in reality, the contiguous counties of [[Worcestershire]] and [[Warwickshire]], south of Birmingham in [[The Midlands]]. Ambridge is possibly based on the village of [[Elmbridge, Worcestershire|Cutnall Green]],<ref name=Cutnall>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/8455995/Have-they-found-the-real-Ambridge.html |title=Have they found the real Ambridge? |last1=Wynne-Jones |first1=Jonathan |last2=Howie |first2=Michael |date=17 April 2011 |website=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Newspapers |access-date=26 February 2018 }}</ref> though various other villages claim to be the inspiration for Ambridge; ''The Bull'', Ambridge's [[pub]], is modelled on The Old Bull in [[Inkberrow]],<ref>Compare Ambridge's [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/gallery_60s_timeline.shtml?select=05 The Bull] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628165347/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/gallery_60s_timeline.shtml?select=05 |date=28 June 2008 }} with Inkberrow's [http://www.inkberrow.org.uk/ The Old Bull].</ref> whereas [[Hanbury, Worcestershire|Hanbury]]'s St Mary the Virgin is often used as a stand-in for Ambridge's [[parish church]], St Stephen's.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/news/anyquestions_transcripts_20060922.shtml | title= Transcript: Any Questions? 22 September 2006 | accessdate=6 January 2008| date=22 September 2006 | publisher= [[BBC Radio 4]] }}</ref><ref>Compare Ambridge's [https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/gallery/ed_emma_will_gallery.shtml?select=10 St Stephen's] with Hanbury's [http://www.hevac-heritage.org/items_of_interest/heating/churches_&_chapels/hanbury_church/hanbury_church.htm St Mary the Virgin].</ref>\n\nOther fictional villages include Penny Hassett, Loxley Barrett,<ref>[http://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/schools/201540/loxley-barrett-primary-school Loxley Barrett Primary School]; goodschoolsguide.co.uk</ref> Darrington, Hollerton, Edgeley, Waterley Cross and Lakey Green. The [[county town]] of Borsetshire is [[Borchester]], and the nearest big city is the [[cathedral city]] of [[Borsetshire|Felpersham]]. Felpersham also has a university. Anywhere further from Ambridge may be referred to humorously with comments such as 'that's on the other side of Felpersham!', but characters do occasionally venture further: several attended the [[Countryside Alliance]] march in London,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2002-09-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20020922&day=0 }}</ref> there have been references to the gay scene in Manchester's [[Canal Street (Manchester)|Canal Street]]. There have been scenes set in other places in the United Kingdom and abroad, with some characters residing overseas such as in South Africa and Hungary.\n\nSince [[Easter Sunday]] 1998, there have been six episodes a week, from Sunday to Friday, broadcast at around 19:03 following the news summary. All except the Friday evening episode are repeated the following day at 14:02. The six episodes are re-run unabridged in the Sunday morning [[omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] at 10:00. On [[Remembrance Sunday]], the Omnibus edition begins at the earlier time of 09:15. This information is available in the press and on the BBC's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 The Archers |publisher=BBC |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|3|27}}, due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] restrictions, weekly programming reduces to five episodes. Friday's episode will cease to be broadcast. The Sunday omnibus will be correspondingly reduced in length to one hour.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Archers characters}}\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Archer family|Archers]]'s [[family farm]], Brookfield, combines arable, dairy, beef, and sheep. It is a typical example of [[mixed farming]] which has been passed down the generations from Dan, the original farmer, to his son Phil and is now co-owned by Phil and Jill's four children: David, who manages it with his wife Ruth; Shula Hebden-Lloyd, owner of the riding stables, was married to  Alistair, a vet; her twin Kenton, runs the village's only pub with his wife Jolene; and the widowed Elizabeth Pargeter. Jill lives in Brookfield with her son David, his wife Ruth and their children Pip, Josh, and Ben.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Aldridge family|Aldridges]] at [[Home farm (agriculture)|Home Farm]]. Brian, who is portrayed as a money-driven [[agribusiness]]man and his wife Jennifer. They have five children: the two Jennifer brought into their marriage: Adam, a farmer married to chef Ian Craig and Debbie a farmer based in Hungary; two born into the marriage, Kate with a family abandoned in South Africa, and Alice married to farrier Chris Carter; and schoolboy Ruairi, Brian's son by one of his affairs. The family also includes Kate's daughter Phoebe and Jennifer's sister Lilian.\n* The Bridge Farm [[List of The Archers characters#The Archer family|Archers]] practise [[organic farming]]. Their operations include a farm shop, a farm caf\u00e9, a [[vegetable box scheme]] and a dairy. Tony and Pat's children are Helen and Tom, and their three grandchildren: Johnny, who is the son of their dead son John; and Henry and Jack.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Pargetter family|Pargetters]], a [[landed gentry]] family who have to make their [[stately home]], Lower Loxley Hall, pay the bills as a public attraction. The family includes Nigel Pargetter's widow, Elizabeth {{n\u00e9e}} Archer, her son Freddie and his twin sister Lily.\n* The [[Joe Grundy|Grundys]], formerly struggling [[tenant farmer]]s who were brought to prominence in the late 1970s and early 1980s as comic characters, but are now seen as doggedly battling adversity.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#The Carter family|Carters]], Neil and Susan. Their son, Chris, is married to Alice Aldridge; their daughter, Emma, has successively married brothers, Will and Edward Grundy.\n* The [[List of The Archers characters#Lynda Snell|Snells]], Lynda, married to the long-suffering Robert, is the butt of many jokes, although her sheer energy makes her a stalwart of village life.\n\n==Ambridge==\n{{See also|List of fictional towns and villages}}\n* ''Arkwright Hall'' is a large Victorian mansion with a 17th-century atmosphere. The building served as a community centre for many years, containing a soundproofed room and field studies centre. Later it fell into disrepair, but was renovated when Jack Woolley leased the mansion to the [[Landmark Trust]]; architect Lewis Carmichael led the restoration of the building to its [[Victorian era|Victorian]] splendour.\n* ''Bridge Farm'' is a {{Convert|168|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm previously on Berrow Estate, but now owned by Pat and Tony Archer. The farm became wholly dedicated to [[organic farming]] in 1984, in a storyline inspired by a scriptwriter's visit to Brynllys farm in [[Ceredigion]], the home of [[Rachel's Organic]].<ref name=Times6847838>{{cite news | title=The Soil Association | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article6847838.ece | work=The Times | location=London | date=25 September 2009| accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> In 2003, Tom Archer began producing his Bridge Farm pork sausages. In early 2013, the family decided to sell their dairy herd and buy organic milk instead and the following year, Tony Archer bought a small [[Angus cattle|Aberdeen Angus]] herd.\n* ''Brookfield Farm'' is a {{Convert|469|acre|ha|adj=on}} mixed farm which was managed by Dan Archer and then by his son Phil. After Phil's retirement in 2001, his son David Archer took over.\n* ''Grange Farm'' was a working farm run by the Grundys until their eviction in 2000. The farmhouse, along with {{Convert|50|acre|ha|}} of land, was sold to Oliver Sterling, who then began \"hobby farming\". He took young Ed Grundy on as cow man and later gave him full responsibility for running the farm.\n* ''Grey Gables'', once a country club, is now a luxurious hotel. The late Caroline Sterling bought it with her husband Oliver Sterling. The hotel boasts a pool, spa, health club and a golf course. Ian Craig is the executive chef.\n* ''Home Farm'' is a {{Convert|1922|acre|ha|adj=on}} farm, by far the largest in Ambridge. In recent years, Home Farm expanded into soft fruit and deer farming.\n* ''Lower Loxley Hall'' is a large 300-year-old country house located just outside Ambridge. It serves primarily as a conference centre. \n* ''The Bull'', the village's only [[Public house|pub]], is perhaps the most recognisable structure in Ambridge\n* ''St. Stephen's Church'', established in 1281, dates back to [[Normans|Norman]] times. The church has undergone many changes over the years, including a number of different vicars. The eight bells are rung by a group led by Neil Carter.\n* Ambridge still has a ''[[Village shop#United Kingdom|village shop and post office]]'', originally thanks to Jack Woolley's philanthropy. The business is now a community shop managed by Susan and run by a team of volunteers.\n* ''Willow Farm'' is owned by the Tucker family. After Betty's death in 2005, the house was divided to accommodate Roy and his family. The [[Agricultural land|farmland]] is home to Neil Carter's pigs.\n\n==Topicality==\nUnlike some soap operas, episodes of ''The Archers'' portray events taking place on the date of broadcast, allowing many topical subjects to be included. Real-life events which can be readily predicted in advance are often written into the script, such as the annual [[Oxford Farming Conference]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/oxford_conference.shtml | title= Oxford Farming Conference | accessdate= 17 February 2008 | publisher= BBC Radio 4 | date= 3 January 2008 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080628092518/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/oxford_conference.shtml | archivedate= 28 June 2008 }}</ref> and the [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-06-27}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20060625&day=2 }}</ref> On some occasions, scenes recorded at these events are planned and edited into episodes shortly before transmission.\n\nMore challengingly for the production team, some significant but unforeseen events require scenes to be rewritten and rerecorded at short notice, such as the death of [[Princess Margaret]] (particularly poignant because she had appeared as herself on the programme),<ref name=\"princess margaret\">{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/princess_margaret.shtml | title= Princess Margaret Remembered | accessdate=17 February 2008| date=10 February 2002 | publisher= BBC Radio 4}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2002-02-10}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20020210&day=0 }}</ref> the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|World Trade Center attacks]],<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-09-12}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010909&day=3 }}</ref> and the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2005-07-11}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20050710&day=1 }}</ref> The events and implications of the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth crisis|2001 foot-and-mouth crisis]] required many \"topical inserts\"<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010218&day=4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-23}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010218&day=5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-02-27}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010225&day=2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2001-03-01}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20010225&day=4 }}</ref> and the rewriting of several storylines.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/drama_in_a_crisis.shtml | title= Drama in a Crisis | accessdate=17 February 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4| date=2 March 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Oliver Sterling, owner of Grange Farm, together with his tenant, Ed Grundy, elected to vaccinate the badgers on their farm in an attempt to prevent the spread of bovine [[tuberculosis]]. The plotline came within weeks of the government confirming a [[Badger culling in the United Kingdom|badger cull trial]].<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01b1g9d/The_Archers_25_01_2012/ | title= The Archers 2012-01-25 | accessdate=2 February 2012| publisher=BBC Radio 4 | date=25 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIt was announced on 29 March 2020 that the programme would include reference to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]] from 4 May onwards.<ref name=\"bbc-29mar20\">{{cite web |title=Changes to The Archers during Coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/coronavirus-archers |website=www.bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Actors==\nUnlike television soaps, ''The Archers'' actors are not held on retainers and work on the series usually for a few days a month. By the nature of the storylines concentrating on particular groups of characters, in any one week out of a cast of about 60, the episodes include approximately 20{{ndash}}30 speaking-characters. Most of the cast do acting work on other projects and can disappear for long periods if they are working on commitments such as films or television series. [[Tamsin Greig]] plays Debbie Aldridge and has appeared on many television series such as ''[[Green Wing]]'', ''[[Love Soup]]'', ''[[Black Books]]'' and ''[[Episodes (TV series)|Episodes]]'', so Debbie manages a farm in [[Hungary]] and her visits to Ambridge are infrequent. [[Felicity Jones]] played Emma Carter from the age of 15 but after a period of studying at [[Wadham College, Oxford]], she gave up the role to move into television and cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-hottest-star-in-hollywood-ndash-who-owes-it-all-to-ambridge-2199000.html|title=The hottest star in Hollywood \u2013 who owes it all to Ambridge|accessdate=10 July 2018|date=31 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome of the actors, when not playing their characters, earn their money through different jobs altogether: Charlotte Connor, when not playing Susan Carter (credited as Charlotte Martin), works full-time as a senior research psychologist at the Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health Foundation; her office is a short walk from [[BBC Birmingham]], and thus she is able to fit her work around recordings.<ref>David Brindle [https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/feb/09/young-people-mental-health-problems-log-on?INTCMP=SRCH \"Young people log on for shared headspace\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 February 2011</ref> Meanwhile, Graham Blockey, who plays Robert Snell, worked till recently as a full-time [[general practitioner]] in Surrey, commuting to and from [[BBC Birmingham]] at weekends and on his days off. He kept his role secret from his patients, for fear of losing their respect, until his retirement from medicine in March 2017.<ref>Matthew Weaver [https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/31/surrey-gp-reveals-archers-character-robert-snell-graham-blockey \"GP reveals his 30-year secret life as Archers character Robert Snell\"], ''The Guardian'', 31 March 2017</ref> Other examples include Felicity Finch (Ruth Archer), who also works as a BBC journalist having travelled on a number of occasions to Afghanistan; and Ian Pepperell (Roy Tucker), who manages a pub in the [[New Forest]].<ref>Chris Arnot, [https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2010/oct/06/60-years-archers-10-things-new \"The Archers at 60\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 October 2010.</ref>\n\n==History==\nA five-episodes pilot series started on [[Whit Monday]], 29 May 1950, and continued throughout that week.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5xGwGj4NgfGRJ1B2mFqg6QM/frequently-asked-questions | title= Frequently Asked Questions | work = The Archers| accessdate=16 June 2019| publisher= BBC Radio 4}}</ref> It was created by [[Godfrey Baseley]] and was broadcast to the English Midlands in the Regional Home Service, as 'a farming [[Dick Barton]]'. Recordings were sent to London, and the BBC decided to commission the series for a longer national run. In the five pilots the Archers owned Wimberton Farm, rather than Brookfield. Baseley subsequently edited ''The Archers'' for 22 years.\n\nSince 1 January 1951, five 15-minute episodes (since 1998, six 12\u00bd-minute episodes) have been transmitted each week, at first on the [[BBC Light Programme]]<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\">Donovan, Paul (1991), ''The Radio Companion''. London: Grafton; p. 8.</ref> and subsequently on the [[BBC Home Service]] (now [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]). Early afternoon repeats of the previous evening's episode began on 14 December 1964. The original scriptwriters were Geoffrey Webb and [[Edward J. Mason]], who were also working on the nightly thriller series about the special agent Dick Barton. The popularity of his adventures partly inspired ''The Archers'', which eventually took over Barton's evening slot. At first, however, the national launch placed the serial at the 'terrible'<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; p.24. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> time of 11.45&nbsp;am, but it moved to Dick Barton's former slot of 6.45&nbsp;pm from Monday, 2 April 1951. An omnibus edition of the week's episodes began on Saturday, 5 January 1952.\n\nOriginally produced with collaborative input from the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]], ''The Archers'' was conceived as a means of disseminating information to farmers and smallholders to help increase productivity in the [[Postwar]] era of [[Rationing in the United Kingdom|rationing]] and food shortages.<ref name=\"Donovan, Paul 1991 p. 8\"/>\n\n''The Archers'' originally centred on the lives of three farmers; Dan Archer, farming efficiently with little cash, Walter Gabriel, farming inefficiently with little cash, and George Fairbrother, a wealthy businessman farming at a loss for tax purposes (which one could do in those days).<ref>Norman Painting, ''Forever Ambridge'' (1975)</ref> The programme was hugely successful, winning the National Radio Awards' 'Most entertaining programme of the Year' award jointly with ''[[Take It from Here]]'' in 1954, and winning the award outright in 1955, in which year the audience was reported to have peaked at 20 million.<ref name=\"The Listener 29 August 1985\">''The Listener'', 29 August 1985.</ref>\n\nAt the late 1950s, despite the growth of television and radio's consequent decline, the programme was still claiming eleven million listeners and was also being transmitted in Canada, Australia, and New Zealand.<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; pp. 75\u201376. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> By the mid-1970s, however, the audience for the two daily broadcasts and the weekend omnibus combined was less than 3 million<ref>Smethurst (1996) ''The Archers'', p. 144.</ref> and in 1976 the BBC Radio Four Review Board twice considered whether or not the programme should be axed.<ref>Hendy, David (2007), ''Life On Air, A history of Radio Four'' Oxford University Press, p. 205. {{ISBN|978-0-19-924881-0}}</ref> The serial's woes at this time were seen to mirror the poor standing of radio drama in general, described as \"a failure to fully shake off the conventions of non-realism which had prevailed in the 1940s and 1950s.\"<ref>Hendy, David (2007) ''Life On Air'', p. 204.</ref>\n\nProgramme chief Jock Gallagher, responsible for ''The Archers'', described these as the serial's \"dog days\".<ref>Hendy (2007), p. 204.</ref> Sweeping editorial reforms followed, included the introduction of women writers (there had been none before 1975), two of whom, Helen Leadbeater and Margaret Phelan, were credited with giving the programme a new definitive style of writing and content, although some listeners complained about their radical feminism.<ref>Glenys Roberts, ''London Evening Standard'', London; 17 March 1983.</ref>\n\nIn 1980 [[Julie Burchill]] commented that the women of Ambridge were no longer stuck with \"the gallons of greengage jam old-guard male scriptwriters kept them occupied with for over twenty years\"; but were 'into post-natal depression and alcoholism on the way to self-discovery'.<ref>Hendy (2007), p, 207.</ref> By the mid-1980s the Radio Four Review Board noted that scripts, directing and acting was \"very good\" and sometimes \"better than ever\".<ref>Hendy (2007), p. 208.</ref> In August 1985 ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'' said that the programme's revival was \"sustained by some of the best acting, direction and writing on radio.\"<ref name=\"The Listener 29 August 1985\"/>\n\n[[Tony Shryane]] MBE was the programme's producer from 1 January 1951 to 19 January 1979. Vanessa Whitburn was the programme's editor from 1992 till 2013. Whitburn took service leave from March to July 2012, when [[John Yorke (producer)|John Yorke]], a former executive producer of ''[[EastEnders]]'', was the acting editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2012/02/acting_archers_editor.html|title=BBC \u2013 The Archers Blog: Acting Archers editor|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> Yorke's arrival prompted charges that the programme was importing the values of ''EastEnders'' to Borsetshire, with fans and commentators complaining that characters were behaving unrealistically simply to generate conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/ourcomments/view/335079|title=EastEnders formula is failing in Ambridge|author=Simon Edge|work=Daily Express|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> This was denied by Yorke, who wrote that he agreed to take over \"on one condition \u2013 that it stayed exactly as it was and that I didn't have to change anything.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2012/06/is_the_archers_going_to_get_da.html|title=BBC \u2013 The Archers Blog: Is The Archers going to get 'darker and bigger? No.|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nVanessa Whitburn was succeeded as editor by [[Sean O'Connor (producer)|Sean O'Connor]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/leisure/showbiz/10593342.O_Connor_takes_Archers__top_job/|title=O'Connor takes Archers' top job|author=Press Association 2014|work=The Argus|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> In September 2016, [[Huw Kennair-Jones]] took over as editor though O'Connor continued to oversee the Helen and Rob storyline until its conclusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5vFGJHJDWPdPSY77RrmtyQD/meet-the-archers-new-editor-huw-kennair-jones| title= Meet The Archers' new editor, Huw Kennair-Jones | accessdate = 18 September 2016 | publisher= BBC}}</ref> Kennair-Jones announced in October 2017 that he was to leave the BBC to work as commissioning editor for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/entries/cab07c63-5403-42be-b16c-9c74875ee062| title= Huw Kennair-Jones steps down as editor of The Archers | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | publisher= BBC| date= 4 October 2017 }}</ref> The short presence of two successive Archers editors in the job led to concerns that there might be a trend of radio drama editing being seen as \"training ground\" for higher-paid positions in TV.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/10/11/archers-will-trouble-editors-keep-poached-tv-star-says/|title= Archers will be in trouble if editors keep being poached by TV, star says |date=11 October 2017|accessdate=9 September 2018|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last1= Furness |first1= Hannah }}</ref> [[Alison Hindell]], the BBC's head of Audio Drama until October 2018, took over as acting editor before<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/sep/13/the-archers-helen-titchner-huw-kennair-jones-bbc-radio-4|title= The Archers: former Sky executive takes over show as Helen Titchener plot ends |date=13 September 2016|accessdate=9 September 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last1= Jackson |first1= Jasper }}</ref> and after<ref name=\"Hindell-Howe\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/hindell-succeed-howe-r4-commissioning-editor-drama-and-fiction-814556|title= Hindell becomes Radio 4 commissioning editor for Drama and fiction |date=19 June 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018|magazine=[[The Bookseller]]}}</ref> Kennair-Jones's time in charge. She effectively swapped with Jeremy Howe when she succeeded him as the BBC's commissioning editor for drama and fiction<ref name=\"Hindell-Howe\" /> and he started as editor of the Archers in late August 2018.<ref>{{cite press release | date = 7 February 2018 | title = Jeremy Howe announced as new editor of The Archers |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/jeremy-howe-archers | publisher = [[BBC]] | access-date= 25 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Howe-starts\"/>\n\nSince 2007, ''The Archers'' has been available as a [[podcast]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qpgr/episodes/downloads |title= Podcasts |work = The Archers | accessdate=10 February 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref>\n\n===Death of Grace Archer===\nOne of the most controversial ''Archers'' episodes was broadcast on 22 September 1955, which coincided with the launch of the UK's first commercial television station. Phil and Grace Archer had been married just a few months earlier, and their blossoming relationship was the talk of the nation. However, searching for a story which would demonstrate some real tragedy among the increasingly unconvincing episode cliff-hangers, Godfrey Baseley had decided that Grace would have to die. The scripts for the week commencing 19 September 1955 were written, recorded, and broadcast on each day, with an \"exercise in topicality\" given as the explanation to the cast. On Thursday, listeners heard the [[sound effect]]s of Grace trying to rescue ''Midnight'', her horse, from a fire in the stable at Brookfield and the crash of a falling [[Beam (structure)|timber beam]].<ref name=\"ep10000\">{{cite episode|title= {{date|1989-05-26}}|number= 10,000|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 }}</ref>\n\nWhether the timing of the episode was a deliberate attempt to overshadow the opening night of the BBC's first commercial rival has been debated ever since. It was certainly planned some months in advance, but it may well be that the actual date of the death was changed during the scriptwriting stage to coincide with [[History of ITV|the launch of Associated-Rediffusion]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Smethurst |title = The Archers| year = 1996 |publisher= |location= | isbn = | page = 63 |chapter = Dead Girls Tell No Tales |quote = Even this presupposes that the BBC realized the impact that the 'death' would have&nbsp;\u2014 and all the evidence is that the BBC was totally taken by surprise.}}</ref> Deliberate or not, the episode attracted widespread media attention, being reported by newspapers around the world.\n\nThis controversy has been parodied twice: in \"[[The Bowmans (Hancock)|The Bowmans]]\", an episode of the television comedy programme ''Hancock'', and in the play ''[[The Killing of Sister George]]'' and [[The Killing of Sister George (film)|its 1968 film adaptation]]. On the 50th anniversary of ITV's launch, [[Ysanne Churchman]], who played Grace, sent them a congratulatory card signed \"Grace Archer\".\n\nIn 1996, William Smethurst recounted a conversation with Baseley in which he reveals his real motivation for killing off Grace Archer: Churchman was encouraging the other actors to join a trade union.<ref>{{cite book |author=Smethurst |title = The Archers |year = 1996 |publisher = |location = |isbn =|page = 64 |chapter = Dead Girls Tell No Tales |quote='She was trying to get the actors to join a trade union,' he told the author of this book, in 1995, 'so I killed her off. Very few of the original actors were professionals. I'd taken them on because they were countrymen with natural country voices. But she was stirring them up and trying to get them to join the actors' union, and saying we should only employ union actors, which would have been fatal.'}}</ref>\n\n===Longevity===\nThe actor [[Norman Painting]] played Phil Archer continuously from the first trial series in 1950 until his death on 29 October 2009. His last ''Archers'' performance was recorded just two days before his death, and was broadcast on 22 November.<ref name=\"bbc-obituary\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8331558.stm|title=Voice of Phil Archer dies aged 85|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> He is cited in ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the longest-serving actor in a single soap opera.<ref name=\"bbc-obituary\"/> Under the pseudonym \"Bruno Milna\", Painting also wrote around 1,200 complete episodes, which culminated in the 10,000th episode.\n\nJune Spencer has played Peggy Archer/Woolley from the pilot episode onwards,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/radio4/junespencer.shtml |title=Biographies: June Spencer OBE, The Archers |accessdate=1 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106073640/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/radio4/junespencer.shtml |archivedate=6 January 2009 }}</ref> though not for all of the period since. According to ''Who's Who in The Archers 2008'',<ref>{{cite book | last = Davies | first = Keri | title = Who's Who in ''The Archers'', 2008 | publisher = [[BBC Books]] | year = 2007 | location = [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] | page = 4 | isbn = 978-1-84607-326-7}}</ref> episode 15,360 was to be broadcast on 1 January 2008.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2008-01-01}}|number= 15,360|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20071230&day=2 }}</ref> Episode 15,000 was broadcast on 7 November 2006.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-11-07}}|number= 15,000|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20061105&day=2 }}</ref>\n\n===Sixtieth anniversary===\nThe Archers reached its 60th anniversary on 1 January 2011 and to mark this achievement, a special half-hour episode was broadcast on Sunday, 2 January, on BBC Radio 4 from 7pm. The episode had been advertised as containing events that would \"shake Ambridge to the core\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/05_may/27/sopps.shtml |title=BBC Statement of Programme Policy for 2010/2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> This phrase even gave rise to the [[initialism]] #SATTC trending on the website Twitter during that weekend as listeners speculated about what might happen, and then reported their views as the story unfolded.\n\nThe main events in the episode were Helen Archer giving birth to her son Henry and Nigel Pargetter falling to his death from the roof of Lower Loxley Hall. This unlikely event provoked interest in the frequency and causes of death in the series. In fact, although the incidence of accidental death and suicide is seven times the national average, the overall mortality rate in Ambridge is almost exactly what would be expected.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d7518 |pmid=22174323 |lay-url=https://www.bmj.com/press-releases/2011/12/15/series-unfortunate-events-morbidity-and-mortality-borsetshire-village |laysource=BMJ |laydate=15 December 2011 |title=A series of unfortunate events? Morbidity and mortality in a Borsetshire village |journal=BMJ |volume=343 |pages=d7518 |year=2011 |last1=Stepney |first1=R. }}</ref>\n\nThe writing out of the character of Nigel caused much controversy among listeners,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2011/01/nigel_pargetter_-_share_your_m.html | title=Nigel Pargetter \u2013 share your memories|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/2011/01/the_archers_editor_on_the_60th.html | title=The Archers editor on the 60th anniversary|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> with a large number of complaints variously expressing dismay at the death of a popular character, concerns over the manner of the dismissal of the actor, belief that the promise to \"shake Ambridge to the core\" had been over-hyped, criticism of the credibility of the script and acting for the anniversary episode, and a perceived unwillingness of the editorial team to engage with these listener complaints.\n \n===Coronavirus===\nThe series initially made no mention of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]]: \" Whereas topical subjects ... have previously been added to scripts, that has not been possible with Coronavirus.\"<ref name=bbc-29mar20 /> It was announced that there would be only five broadcasts a week from 27 March \u2013 the Friday broadcast omitted \u2013 and that enough recordings were in hand until the end of April.<ref name=\"turner\">{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Camilla |title=The Archers becomes latest victim of coronavirus as Coronation Street and Emmerdale to stop filming |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/22/archers-becomes-latest-victim-coronavirus-coronation-street/ |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> From 4 May, the programmes will have been recorded in the actors' homes and will include references to the pandemic with \"fewer characters who will be sharing more of their private thoughts with the listener\". The series editor Jeremy Howe said, \"Coronavirus will be reflected in ''The Archers'' from May ... in a way that the programme's many loyal listeners might expect.\"<ref name=\"BBC-29mar20\">{{cite web |title=Changes to The Archers during Coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/coronavirus-archers |website=www.bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nThe programme has tackled many serious, contemporary social issues: rural [[drug addiction]]; rape, including [[Marital rape|rape in marriage]]; inter-racial relationships; [[direct action]] against [[Genetically modified food|genetically modified]] crops and badger culling; family break-ups; and [[civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships]], and a family being threatened by a gang of farm thieves. There has been criticism from conservative commentators, such as [[Peter Hitchens]] in 1999<ref>Peter Hitchens (2000) [1999], ''[[The Abolition of Britain]]'', pp. 262\u201364, Quartet (revised edition)</ref> that the series has become a vehicle for liberal and left-wing values and agendas, with characters behaving out of character to achieve those goals. However, one of the show's charms is to make much out of everyday, small concerns, such as the possible closure of the village shop, the loss and rediscovery of a pair of spectacles,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2005-06-07}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20050605&day=2 }}</ref> competitive [[marmalade]]-making, or nonsense such as a '[[spile]] [[wikt:trosh|troshing]]' competition,<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2000-08-11}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 }}</ref> rather than the large-scale and improbable events that form the plots of many soap operas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mahoney|first=Elisabeth|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/apr/16/radio.tvandradioarts|title=Radio review: The Archers|work=The Guardian|date=16 April 2008|accessdate=16 April 2008 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/9445689/Archers-loses-400000-listeners-amid-controversy-over-sexed-up-storylines.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Archers loses 400,000 listeners amid controversy over sexed-up storylines |date=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some of the actors, and confirmed in the writings of Godfrey Baseley, in its early days the show was used as a conduit for educational announcements from the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Agriculture]], one actor reading an announcement almost verbatim to another. Direct involvement of the government ended in 1972.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Salute to The Archers|journal=Agriculture: The Journal of the Ministry of Agriculture|volume=79|year=1972|page=43}}</ref> The show has reacted within a day to agricultural emergencies such as outbreaks of [[foot and mouth disease]] which affect farmers nationwide when livestock movements are restricted.\n\n==Cameo appearances==\nMany famous people have made [[cameo appearance]]s on the programme:\n* [[Princess Margaret]] and the [[Gerald Grosvenor, 6th Duke of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]] appeared in 1984 in connection with a fashion show to commemorate the centenary of the [[NSPCC]].<ref name=\"princess margaret\"/>\n* Dame [[Judi Dench]] made an appearance as the (hitherto usually silent) Pru Forrest in 1989 for the 10,000th episode. [[Terry Wogan]] was featured and [[Esther Rantzen]] was responsible for the [[sound effect]]s.<ref name=\"ep10000\"/>\n* Radio presenter [[John Peel]] appeared as himself in 1991.<ref>{{cite news | title = Peel's life away from music | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3956119.stm | publisher=BBC News|date =26 October 2004|accessdate =5 January 2008}}</ref>\n* Gardener [[Alan Titchmarsh]] judged Ambridge's entries in the [[National Gardens Scheme]] open gardens competition in May 2003.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2003-05-26}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20030525&day=1 }}</ref>\n* Radio presenter [[Chris Moyles]] appeared in June 2004 as a random customer\u2014and suspected [[National Pub of the Year]] judge\u2014in The Bull.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/moyles_visit.shtml |title= Chris Moyles braves The Bull |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |date= 10 June 2004 |publisher= BBC Radio 4 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060314092916/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/backstage/moyles_visit.shtml |archivedate= 14 March 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2004-06-14}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20040613&day=1 }}</ref>\n* Comedian [[Griff Rhys Jones]] appeared as himself in July 2004, when he was drafted into Lynda's campaign to restore the Cat and Fiddle pub.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2004-07-14}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20040711&day=3 }}</ref>\n* [[Zandra Rhodes]] played herself in an episode in September 2006 in connection with a charity fashion show.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thearchers.co.uk/archers/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=119&ItemID=2442&tabIndex=0 |title= Introducing Ms Zandra Rhodes |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |date= 11 September 2006 |publisher= Archers Addicts |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071203075126/http://www.thearchers.co.uk/archers/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=119&ItemID=2442&tabIndex=0 |archivedate= 3 December 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2006-09-22}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20060917&day=5 }}</ref>\n* [[Robert Winston]] appeared as a [[fertility]] specialist consulted by Hayley and Roy Tucker in January<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-01-02}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20061231&day=2 }}</ref> and February 2007.<ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-02-07}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20070204&day=3 }}</ref>\n* [[Mike Gatting]] appeared in September 2007 at the centre of a misunderstanding between Sid and Jolene Perks during the [[npower (UK)|npower]] Village Cup final at [[Lord's Cricket Ground]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/09_september/07/archers.shtml |title= From The Ashes to The Archers |accessdate=5 January 2008|date=7 September 2007|publisher= BBC Press Office }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title= {{date|2007-09-09}}|series= The Archers |network= BBC Radio 4 |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/archive_synopsis.shtml?week=20070909&day=0 }}</ref>\n* Crime novelist [[Colin Dexter]] made a cameo in 2010.<ref>Andrew French, [http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/8301866.Morse_author_meets_the_Archers/ \"Morse author meets the Archers\"], ''Oxford Mail'', 30 July 2010.</ref>\n* [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] appeared on 16 February 2011 in connection with the [[National Osteoporosis Society]]'s 25th anniversary as well as the show's 60th anniversary.\n* In 2011, a recording of the show ''[[Gardeners' Question Time]]'' was followed by a special recording session in which Archers characters, notably Brian Aldridge, took part asking questions of the regular panellists while sitting with the audience.\n* [[Sir Bradley Wiggins]] appeared in an April 2014 episode, presenting prizes at the Ambridge [[Sport Relief]] Rough and Tumble event Challenge.\n* [[Kirstie Allsopp]] appeared in July 2014 to open the village fete.\n* In August 2014, the [[Pet Shop Boys]] were last-minute headliners at the music festival Loxfest.\n* [[Anneka Rice]] has appeared twice in Ambridge; in March 1993 and in March 2016.\n* In September 2016, in an hour-long episode concluding a highly publicised storyline in which Helen Titchener had stabbed her abusive husband Rob, some notable names guest starred as jury members, including [[Eileen Atkins]], [[Catherine Tate]] and [[Nigel Havers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37319113 |title=The Archers: Famous names on jury for Helen Titchener's trial|publisher=BBC News |date= 9 September 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Others who have made appearances include [[Britt Ekland]], [[Humphrey Lyttelton]] (1956), [[Dame Edna Everage]] and [[Antony Gormley]] (2009).\n\n==Theme tune==\nThe [[theme tune]] of ''The Archers'' is called \"[[Barwick Green]]\" and is a [[maypole dance]] from the suite ''My Native Heath'', written in 1924 by the Yorkshire composer [[Arthur Wood (composer)|Arthur Wood]]. The Sunday [[Omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] broadcast of ''The Archers'' starts with a more [[Pastoral|rustic]], [[accordion]]-arranged rendition by [[The Yetties]].<ref>{{cite book|last=The Yetties|title=Upmarket|year=1997|id=Decca SKL 5282|nopp=true|page=Track 1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/60-things-you-never-knew-you-wanted-to-know-about-the-archers-2173365.html|title=60 things you never knew you wanted to know about The Archers|last=Gonsalves|first=Rebecca|date=1 January 2011|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref> The theme for [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]]'s ''The Archers'' spinoff, ''[[Ambridge Extra]]'', is a version arranged by [[Bellowhead]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2011/apr/05/tv-theme-tunes|title=TV theme tunes: don't mess with the best|last=Heritage|first=Stuart|date=5 April 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[library music]] recording of Barwick Green was used for the pilot and during the early years of the national version, because a bid by Godfrey Baseley to have a special theme composed had been turned down on the grounds of cost, put at \u00a3250-\u00a3300.<ref>Smethurst, William (1996), ''The Archers: The True Story''. London: Michael O'Mara Books; p.20. {{ISBN|1-85479-689-5}}</ref> However, once the serial had become undeniably established, a new recording of Barwick Green was authorised and performed by the BBC Midland Light Orchestra on 24 March 1954.<ref>BBC Gramophone Library</ref> This mono recording was also accompanied by four movements entitled \"A Village Suite\", composed by Kenneth Pakeman to complement Barwick Green. Excerpts from these movements were then used for a time as bridging music between scenes. The 1954 recordings were never made available to the public and their use was restricted even inside the BBC, partly because of an agreement with the Musicians' Union.\n\nIn 1992, the theme was re-recorded in stereo, retaining the previous arrangements. The venue was Symphony Hall in Birmingham, the conductor Ron Goodwin, producer David Welsby and the sound mixer Norman McLeod. The slightly different sound mixing and more leisurely tempo reportedly led some listeners to consider the new version inferior, specifically that it lacked \"brio\", although the BBC publicised the fact that the orchestra contained some of the musicians who had played in the previous recording, including Harold Rich (piano) and Norman Parker (percussion). {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n[[Robert Robinson (broadcaster)|Robert Robinson]] once compared the tune to \"the genteel abandon of a lifelong teetotaller who has suddenly taken to drink\". {{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} On [[April Fool's Day]] 2004 both ''[[The Independent]]'' and ''[[The Today Programme]]'' claimed that BBC executives had commissioned composer [[Brian Eno]] to record an electronic version of \"Barwick Green\" as a replacement for the current theme,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tumti-tumti-tumti-tum-kerrang-ambridge-in-uproar-over-enos-newwave-theme-tune-568412.html |title= Tum-ti tum-ti tum-ti tum... kerrang. Ambridge in uproar over Eno's 'new-wave' theme tune |accessdate=17 February 2008 |date=1 April 2004 | newspaper=[[The Independent]]| location=London | first=David | last=Lister}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/today/reports/arts/archers_20040401.shtml | title= New Archers Theme Tune |accessdate=17 February 2008| date=1 April 2004 | publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref> while comedian [[Billy Connolly]] included in his act the joke that the theme was so typically British that it should be the [[national anthem of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i9nnnM-__JQ|title=Billy Connelly : National Anthem|last=Max Kellar|date=1 March 2008|accessdate=10 July 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, comedian [[Rainer Hersch]] conducted the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]] in a performance of the theme, live from the [[Royal Festival Hall]] to a listening [[BBC Radio 3]] audience in an attempt to confuse them. He then went on to show how similar it is to \"[[Montagues and Capulets]]\" \u2013 \"Dance of the Knights\" \u2013 from ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' by [[Sergei Prokofiev]], claiming that this was a result of Russian spies going through the BBC's rubbish bins looking for the scripts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HCVPgrQTHO0|title=Funny! 'The Archers' and 'Dance of the Knights'|via=YouTube|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Serious events===\nAt times, a cliffhanger involving the death of a major character or a disaster was marked by the traditional closing theme being replaced by the final dramatic section of ''[[Barwick Green]]'' involving trombones, cymbals and the closing bars of the signature tune \u2013 known as the \"doom music\" to some fan groups.<ref>[https://ambridgereporter.org.uk/nicknames.html See 'doom music' in 'Archers phrases']</ref> This tradition has been dropped more recently, with events such as the death of Nigel Pargetter being followed by the normal closing music despite the gravity of the incident. This has irritated some followers, who consider the jollity of the normal segment inappropriate in such circumstances.<ref>[http://www.lowfield.co.uk/archers/rip.html Seek 'doom music' in this]</ref>\n\nA brief extract from ''[[The Dream of Gerontius]]'' was played following the death of Phil Archer. When John Archer died no music was played.\n\nThere was a nod to ''The Archers'' in [[2012 Summer Olympics opening ceremony#Frankie and June say...thanks Tim .2821:52.E2.80.9322:09.29|the opening ceremony of the Olympic Games]] in London on 27 July 2012, where the theme tune was played at the beginning of a segment celebrating British culture: the sound of a radio could be heard being tuned in as ''Barwick Green'' was played.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/jul/28/olympic-games-opening-ceremony-british | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Marina | last=Hyde | title=Olympic Games opening ceremony: irreverent and idiosyncratic | date=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Casting ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Actor\n! Character\n! Duration\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[June Spencer]]\n| [[Peggy Woolley]]\n| 1950\u20131953, 1961\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lesley Saweard\n| [[Christine Barford]]\n| 1953\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Patricia Greene]]\n| [[Jill Archer]]\n| 1957\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Angela Piper\n|[[Jennifer Aldridge]]\n|1963\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Judy Bennett]]\n|[[Shula Hebden-Lloyd]]\n|1971\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Brian Hewlett\n|[[Neil Carter (The Archers)|Neil Carter]]\n|1973\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Patricia Gallimore\n|[[Pat Archer]]\n|1974\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Terry Molloy]]\n|[[Mike Tucker (The Archers)|Mike Tucker]]\n|1974\u20131977, 1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Charles Collingwood (actor)|Charles Collingwood]]\n|Brian Aldridge\n|1975\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Hedli Niklaus\n|Kathy Perks\n|1977, 1978\u20131981, 1983\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Trevor Harrison\n|Eddie Grundy\n|1979\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Heather Bell\n|Clarrie Grundy\n|1979\u20131988, 2013\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Timothy Bentinck\n|David Archer\n|1982\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Charlotte Martin\n|Susan Carter\n|1983\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Alison Dowling\n|Elizabeth Pargetter\n|1984\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Edward Kelsey]]\n|Joe Grundy\n|1985\u20132019\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Carole Boyd]]\n|Lynda Snell\n|1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Graham Blockey\n|Robert Snell\n|1986\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Felicity Finch]]\n|[[Ruth Archer]]\n|1987\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Philip Molloy\n|Will Grundy\n|1989\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Tamsin Greig]]\n|Debbie Aldridge\n|1991\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[William Gaminara]]\n|Richard Locke\n|1992\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Souad Faress\n|Usha Franks\n|1994\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ian Pepperell\n|Roy Tucker\n|1995\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Buffy Davis\n|Jolene Archer\n|1996\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Jamila Massey|Jamilla Massey]]\n|Aunty Satya Khanna\n|1996\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Robin Pirongs\n|[[Sam Batton]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Eric Allan]]\n|Bert Fry\n|1997\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Kim Durham\n|Matt Crawford\n|1997\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Michael Lumsden\n|Alistair Lloyd\n|1998\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Annabelle Dowler]]\n|Kirsty Miller\n|1999\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Louiza Patikas]]\n|Helen Titchener\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Richard Attlee\n|Kenton Archer\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Barry Farrimond\n|Ed Grundy\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Robert Lister\n|Lewis Charmichael\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Joanna Van Kampen\n|Fallon Rogers\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Michael Cochrane]]\n|Oliver Sterling\n|2000\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Sunny Ormonde\n|Lillian Bellamy\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ryan Kelly\n|Jack McCreary\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Hollie Chapman]]\n|Alice Carter\n|2001\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Andrew Wincott\n|Adam Macy\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |John Telfer\n|Rev Alan Franks\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Stephen Kennedy]]\n|Ian Craig\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mona Hammond\n|Mabel Thompson\n|2003\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lorraine Coady\n|Hayley Tucker\n|2006\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[John Rowe (actor)|John Rowe]]\n|Prof Jim Lloyd\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Julia Hills]]\n|Annabelle Schrivener\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Arthur Hughes\n|Ruairi Donovan\n|2007\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Helen Longworth]]\n|Hannah Riley\n|2008\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Emerald O'Hanrahan]]\n|Emma Carter\n|2009\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Lucy Morris\n|Phoebe Aldridge\n|2010\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[David Hargreaves (actor)|David Hargreaves]]\n|Alf Grundy\n|2012\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |James Cartwright\n|Harrison Burns\n|2013\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Daisy Badger\n|Pip Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Angus Imrie]]\n|Josh Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |David Troughton\n|Tony Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Simon Williams\n|Justin Elliott\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Tom Gibbons\n|Johnny Phillips\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |William Troughton\n|Tom Archer\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Eleanor Bron\n|Carol Tregorran\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Perdita Avery\n|Kate Madikane\n|2014\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Toby Laurence\n|Freddie Pargetter\n|2016\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Isobel Middleton\n|Anna Tregorran\n|2016\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Katie Redford\n|Lily Pargetter\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Will Howard\n|Dan Hebden-Lloyd\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Andy Hockley\n|Philip Moss\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Wilf Scolding\n|Christopher Carter\n|2017\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ben Norris\n|Ben Archer\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Mogali Masuku\n|Noluthando Madikane\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Ania Sowinski\n|Lexi Viktorova\n|2018\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Mali Harries]]\n|Natasha Archer\n|2018\u2013\n|}\n\n==''Ambridge Extra''==\n[[BBC Radio 4 Extra]] ran an occasional short supplement, ''[[Ambridge Extra]]'', between 2011 and 2013, featuring characters away from the Ambridge environs. Series 1 and 2 had 26 episodes and series 3, 4 and 5 had 20. The reason offered for non-renewal was limited resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thearchers/posts/Ambridge-Extra-on-Radio-4-Extra|title=BBC \u2013 Blogs \u2013 The Archers \u2013 Ambridge Extra on Radio 4 Extra|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 December 2014|date=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Fan clubs==\nTwo organisations dedicated to the programme were established in the 1990s. Archers Addicts was the official body, run by members of the cast. The club had five thousand members<ref>Clive Aslet, et al [http://www.countrylife.co.uk/property/article/453925/Why-we-love-The-Archers.html \"Why we love The Archers\"], ''Country Life'', 7 May 2010.</ref> and an online shop where Archers memorabilia was sold under licence. It closed as a club on 31 December 2013 but still has a Facebook page and Twitter feed. Archers Anarchists was formed some time later, objecting to the \"castist\" assumptions propagated by the BBC, and claiming that the characters are real.\n\nThe [[usenet]] [[newsgroup]] uk.media.radio.archers<ref>[https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/uk.media.radio.archers uk.media.radio.archers on Google Groups]</ref> (referred to as UMRA by its users, who call themselves umrats) has been running since 1995. Its users include experts on subjects covered by the programme, such as the many aspects of farming, the running of small businesses, [[Campanology|bell ringing]]; lengthy discussions ensue \u2013 as well as light-hearted matters, and plot speculation. Various gatherings occur where umrats come together. The first were a series of about ten annual barbecues.<ref>[http://www.leverton.org/blosxom/Usenet/Umra/Umra%20Barbeque%202000/ UMRA 2000 barbecue]</ref> The first was attended by [[Carole Boyd]] ([[Lynda Snell]])]. They have included participants from Europe and the Americas. It has nicknames for many of the main Archers characters, such as S'aint for Shula. There are nicknames for most of the regular participants).<ref>[https://ambridgereporter.org.uk/nicknames.html UMRA nicknames and related matters]</ref> Due perhaps to it being initially more accessible in academia, the discussions can be quite detailed, though UMRA considers itself to be a friendly and welcoming group, where in particular [[flamewars]] and the like are not welcome. Despite the general decline of usenet<ref>discussion on the decline of usenet[[Usenet#Decline]]</ref> with the advent of trendier media such as Facebook and Twitter, UMRA remains a very active newsgroup compared to many. Its one-time T-shirts<ref>[http://www.clothandclay.co.uk/umra/bbq2002/bbq0208.htm UMRA T-shirt, 2002]</ref> and mugs bore the legend (in yellow on \"Barwick Green\", of course) \"An everyday story of internet folk.\"<ref>[http://www.clothandclay.co.uk/umra/index.htm UMRA logo]</ref>\n\nThe Academic Archers, founded in 2016, is a community of fans who share an academic approach to the programme. It organises an annual conference at which papers are presented which draw on academic expertise along with enjoyment. Papers from these have been published as ''The Archers in Fact and Fiction: Academic Analyses of Life in Rural Borsetshire'' (2016, Peter Lang:{{ISBN|9781787071193}}), ''Custard, Culverts and Cake'' (2017, Emerald: {{ISBN|9781787432864}} and ''Gender, Sex and Gossip: Women in The Archers'' (2019, Emerald: {{ISBN|9781787699489}} ) The group aims to be \"curious, generous and joyful\".<ref name=academic>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=Academic Archers|url=http://www.academicarchers.net|access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=rosefield>{{cite news|work=New Statesman|last=Rosefield|first=Hannah|URL=https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2016/03/what-we-learned-first-academic-archers-conference|title=What we learned from the first academic Archers conference|date=28 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=tickle>{{cite news|work=The Guardian|last=Tickle|first=Louise|URL= https://amp-theguardian-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/amp.theguardian.com/education/2018/feb/13/archers-conference-ticket-radio-4-ambridge?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Feducation%2F2018%2Ffeb%2F13%2Farchers-conference-ticket-radio-4-ambridge |title=The Archers academic conference: hot ticket for Radio 4 fans and insurgency experts|date=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Parallels==\nIn 1994, the [[BBC World Service]] in Afghanistan began broadcasting ''Naway Kor, Naway Jwand'' (\"New Home, New Life\"), an everyday story of country folk incorporating pieces of useful information. Although the useful information was more likely to concern unexploded [[land mine]]s and [[opium]] addiction than the latest modern farming techniques, the inspiration and model of ''Naway Kor, Naway Jwand'' was ''The Archers'', and the initial workshopping with Afghan writers included an ''Archers'' scriptwriter.<ref>{{cite news | authorlink = Emma Brockes | first = Emma | last= Brockes | title = A long way from Ambridge | url = https://www.theguardian.com/waronterror/story/0,1361,579231,00.html | work =The Guardian | date =23 October 2001 |accessdate =16 February 2008| location=London}}</ref> A 1997 study found that listeners to the soap opera were significantly less likely to be injured by a mine than non-listeners.<ref>Neil Andersson, Charles Whitaker, Aparna Swaminathan. [http://www.ciet.org/en/documents/projects_library_docs/200652984313.pdf ''Afghanistan: The 1997 National Mine Awareness Evaluation''], [http://www.ciet.org/en/ CIET international] 1998. [http://www.ciet.org/en/documents/projects_library_docs/2006522121941.pdf \"Executive summary\"]. Retrieved 17 November 2006.</ref>\n\nIn [[Rwanda]], the BBC World Service's [[Rwanda-Rundi]] service has been broadcasting the Archers-inspired soap opera ''Urunana'' (\"Hand in Hand\") since 1999.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.developments.org.uk/articles/health-soap-opera/ | title= Country life | accessdate= 16 February 2008 | first= Josephine Irene | last= Uwamariya | author2= Kalisa Narcisse | work= Developments | publisher= [[Department for International Development]] | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080113182253/http://www.developments.org.uk/articles/health-soap-opera/ | archivedate= 13 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.comminit.com/en/node/118365 | title= Urunana Radio Soap&nbsp;\u2014 Rwanda | accessdate= 16 February 2008 | date= 14 August 2003 | publisher= The Communication Initiative Network | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110119174446/http://comminit.com/en/node/118365 | archivedate= 19 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''The Archers'' was the model for the Russian radio soap opera ''Dom 7, Podyezd 4'' (\"House 7, Entrance 4\"),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tve.org/sisters/Domsyem.html |title= Dom Syem, Podjezd Chetirie |accessdate= 5 January 2008 |first= Joan |last= Connolly |date= 22 October 2005 |publisher= [[Television Trust for the Environment]] |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071022202735/http://www.tve.org/sisters/Domsyem.html |archivedate= 22 October 2007 }}</ref> on which the former [[UK Prime Minister]], [[Tony Blair]], once made a cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.brandrepublic.com/login/News/97015/ | title= Broadcast: Tune in to the power of the viewing public |accessdate=5 January 2008| first= Jemimah |last=Bailey |date=17 October 1997 | work= Brand Republic }}</ref>\n\n==Parodies==\n[[Tony Hancock]] starred in the Galton and Simpson spoof \"[[The Bowmans]]\" in an episode of [[BBC Television]]'s ''[[Hancock's Half Hour]]''.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3_X6Y4q3vwQ \"The Bowmans\"], ''Hancock's Half Hour''</ref>\n\n[[Ned Sherrin]] produced a short 1973 film called ''The Cobblers of Umbridge''. The cast included [[Joan Sims]], [[Lance Percival]], [[Roy Kinnear]], [[Derek Griffiths]] and [[John Fortune]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069893/|title=The Cobblers of Umbridge (TV Movie 1973)|date=28 December 1973|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[John Finnemore (writer)|John Finnemore's Souvenir Programme]]'' has parodied ''The Archers'' with its recurring \"The Archers Accidentally\" sketches;<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.is/20140530205122/http://www.bbc-now.co.uk/programmes/p01pgzx0 | title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 John Finnemore's Souvenir Programme, Series 1, Episode \u2026| date=30 May 2014}}</ref> the sketches claim to portray ''The Archers'' the way it sounds to people who only listen to the show inadvertently.\n\nThe radio series of ''[[Dead Ringers (comedy)|Dead Ringers]]'' has frequently parodied characters from ''The Archers'', including a special edition.\n\nThe subtitle was parodied by [[Bill Tidy]] in his long-running cartoon of ''[[The Cloggies]]'', \"an Everyday Saga in the Life of Clog Dancing Folk\", which ran in the satirical magazine ''[[Private Eye]]'', and later in ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]''.\n\n==Books and audiobooks==\n\n===Reference works===\n* ''Forever Ambridge&nbsp;\u2014 25 Years of The Archers'' (1975) by [[Norman Painting]] ASIN B0012UT8XM\n* ''The Book of The Archers'' (1994) by [[Patricia Greene]], [[Charles Collingwood (actor)|Charles Collingwood]] and Hedli Niklaus {{ISBN|0-7181-3849-X}}\n* ''The Archers: The True Story'' (1996) by William Smethurst {{ISBN|1-85833-620-1}}\n* ''The Archers Encyclopaedia'' (2001) by Joanna Toye and Adrian Flynn {{ISBN|0-563-53718-3}}, published to coincide with the 50th anniversary of ''The Archers''\n* ''Who's Who in The Archers 2008'' by [[Keri Davies]]. {{ISBN|1-84607-326-X}}\n* ''Who's Who in The Archers 2011'' by Graham Harvey. {{ISBN|978-1-849-90015-7}}\n* ''The Archers Miscellany'' (2010) by Joanna Toye. {{ISBN|978-1-84607-754-8}}\n* ''The Road to Ambridge'' (2010) by [[June Spencer]]. {{ISBN|978-1-907532-25-2}}\n* ''The Archers Archives'' (2010) by Simon Frith & Chris Arnot. {{ISBN|978-1-84990-013-3}}\n* ''Borsetshire Life'' (2011). The county magazine. {{ISBN|978-1-902685-14-4}} see [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308063938/http://www.silkpress.co.uk/borsetshire-life.html borsetshire-life]\n\n===Novelisations===\n* ''The Archers'' by Jock Gallagher\n* ''Ambridge Summer'' by [[Keith Miles]] (1975). {{ISBN|0-85523-065-7}}\n** ''The Archers: To The Victor The Spoils'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20599-7}}\n** ''The Archers: Return to Ambridge'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20606-3}}\n** ''The Archers: Borchester Echoes'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-20607-1}}\n** ''The Archers: Omnibus Edition'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-36001-1}}\n* ''The Ambridge Chronicles'' by Joanna Toye\n** ''The Archers 1951\u20131967: Family Ties'' (1998). {{ISBN|0-563-38397-6}}\n** ''The Archers 1968\u20131986: Looking For Love'' (1999). {{ISBN|0-563-55125-9}}\n** ''The Archers 1987\u20132000: Back to the Land'' (2000). {{ISBN|0-563-53701-9}}\n** ''The Archers 1951\u20131967: Family Ties'' (1998, audiobook, narrated by [[Miriam Margolyes]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55714-1}}\n** ''The Archers 1968\u20131986: Looking For Love'' (1999, audiobook, narrated by [[Stella Gonet]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55813-X}}\n** ''The Archers 1987\u20132000: Back to the Land'' (2000, audiobook, narrated by [[Stephanie Cole]]). {{ISBN|0-563-55818-0}}\n* In 1975, Tandem published a prequel novel about Ambridge in the early 1900s\n** ''Spring at Brookfield'' by [[Brian Hayles]] (1975). {{ISBN|978-0-426-16520-0}}\n\n===Published audio episodes===\n* ''Vintage Archers''\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 1'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-22586-6}}\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 2'' (1988). {{ISBN|0-563-22704-4}}\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volume 3'' (1998). {{ISBN|0-563-55740-0}} (contains several \"lost episodes\" which have been digitally restored)\n** ''The Archers: The Wedding'' Jack and Peggy tie the knot\n** ''Vintage Archers: Volumes 1\u20133'' (2001). {{ISBN|0-563-38281-3}}\n* ''Ambridge Affairs''\n** ''Ambridge Affairs: Love Triangles'' (2007). {{ISBN|1-4056-7733-3}}\n** ''Ambridge Affairs: Heartache at Home Farm'' (2007). {{ISBN|1-4056-8785-1}}\n\n===Maps===\nIn addition to books and audiobooks, purported maps of Ambridge and Borsetshire have been published.<ref>{{cite book | last = Humphreys | first = John | title = Archers Addicts Official Map of Ambridge | date = 23 September 1994 | publisher = Old House Books | isbn = 978-1-873590-08-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers/wallpaper/ | title= Wallpaper |work =The Archers | accessdate=6 January 2008| publisher=BBC Radio 4}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nAn episode of ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'', broadcast on [[BBC Four]] on 1 January 2007, focused on ''The Archers''. It was narrated by [[Stephen Fry]] and included interviews with current actors and scriptwriters.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/documentaries/features/archers.shtml | title= Arena: The Archers | accessdate= 5 January 2006 | first= Emily | last= Kennedy | year= 2006 | work= BBC Four | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070117231218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/documentaries/features/archers.shtml | archivedate= 17 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of longest-serving soap opera actors]]\n* [[List of radio soaps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Sanderson, Ian (1998) ''The Archers Anarchists' A \u2013 Z''. London: Boxtree {{ISBN|0-7522-2442-5}} (the author founded the Archers Anarchists in 1995)\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/archers}}\n\n{{Soap operas in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n{{BBC Radio 4}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archers, The}}\n[[Category:British radio soap operas]]\n[[Category:1951 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:BBC Birmingham productions]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 4 programmes]]\n[[Category:The Archers| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dbd68", "label": "safe", "comment": "episode count update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Archers"}
{"title_page": "Sanguis Venenatus", "text_new": "{{coi|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Elegy for strings by Andrew March in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to tainted blood.}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Sanguis Venenatus''\n| translation         = Tainted blood\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Andrew March]]\n| catalogue           = \n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[String orchestra#repertoire|Music for strings]]\n| composed            = {{start date|2009}}\n| premiere_date       = {{Start date|2010|03|20|df=y}} \n| premiere_location   = [[Todmorden]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| premiere_conductor  = Nick Concannon Hodges\n| Premiere_performers = Todmorden Orchestra\n| publisher           = \n| published           = \n| first_recording     = {{Start date|2011|07|09|df=y}} Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| form                =  [[Ternary form]]\n| duration            = {{Duration|m=5|s=30}}\n| scoring             = [[String orchestra]]\n| misc                = Written in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to contaminated blood\n}}\n\n'''''Sanguis Venenatus''''' is an elegy for strings by English composer [[Andrew March]] written in memory of [[haemophiliac]]s (and others) affected by the [[United Kingdom tainted blood scandal|Tainted Blood Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday \u2013 Verity Sharp, Late Junction \u2013 BBC Radio 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06g6456|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanguis Venenatus \u2013 Andrew March & Moravian Philharmonic Strings Song \u2013 BBC Music|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802015204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n3x4nm|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Composers \u2013 Alliance Publications, Inc.|url=http://www.apimusic.org/march-andrew-b.1973.html|website=www.apimusic.org|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenberg |first=Donald |date=March 2013 |title=Sounds of America |url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/34724/page/9|work=Gramophone |location=UK |access-date=2020-04-19|quote=''Slow, aching lines and mild dissonances also inhabit Andrew March\u2032s intensely felt \u2033Sanguis venenatus\u2033.''}}</ref><ref name=\"Todmorden1\">{{cite web|title=Reviews \u2013 Todmorden Orchestra|url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/|website=Todmorden Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item = Sanguis Venenatus |item-url =https://rcm.koha-ptfs.co.uk/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=249942 |type = Audio CD |item-id = |date = 2012 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = NV5895 Navona Records |collection = In Dimensions : works for string orchestra|repository = RCM Library Catalogue|institution = Royal College of Music |location = London |oclc= |accession= |ref=CD11802}}</ref> The elegy was included in a service on 30 March, 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/4247/chronically-sick-disabled-persons-act-service.pdf |title=A service to mark the 40th anniversay of the coming into effect of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 March 2011 |website= |publisher=Westminster Abbey |access-date=2020-04-18 |quote=}}</ref> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the UK legislation&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970). ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was dedicated to the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]], to recognise his long\u2013standing support and advocacy for persons with haemophilia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> \n\n==Composition==\nIn 2009, Andrew March completed a cycle of 10 string quartets based on the characteristics of [[diurnal]] [[birds of prey]]. The fifth piece, entitled ''Elegy for an Unsuspecting [[Red phalarope|Phalarope]]'' was inspired by the image of a huge [[Common buzzard|buzzard]] snatching a small grey [[Wader|wading bird]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> The photograph, which appeared in [[The Times]], was taken by two birdwatchers, Paul Freestone and Tim Twiggs at [[St Gothian Sands]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=de Bruxelles|first=Simon |date=16 January 2009 |title=Horrified twitchers watch as starving buzzard kills rare phalarope |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/horrified-twitchers-watch-as-starving-buzzard-kills-rare-phalarope-53hkjvdddgc |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |date=16 January 2009 |title=Buzzard kills rare visitor to British shores |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/jan/16/wildlife-cornwall |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This image was used by March as a poignant metaphor for the disaster which befell thousands of haemophiliacs through [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood products]] with which they were treated.<ref name=\"Todmorden1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W4gy-7IlUqg YouTube, (''Sanguis Venenatus'')]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n[[Category:Music with dedications]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n[[Category:2009 compositions]]\n\n{{Music-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Elegy for strings by Andrew March in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to tainted blood.}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Sanguis Venenatus''\n| translation         = Tainted blood\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Andrew March]]\n| catalogue           = \n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[String orchestra#repertoire|Music for strings]]\n| composed            = {{start date|2009}}\n| premiere_date       = {{Start date|2010|03|20|df=y}} \n| premiere_location   = [[Todmorden]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| premiere_conductor  = Nick Concannon Hodges\n| Premiere_performers = Todmorden Orchestra\n| publisher           = \n| published           = \n| first_recording     = {{Start date|2011|07|09|df=y}} Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| form                =  [[Ternary form]]\n| duration            = {{Duration|m=5|s=30}}\n| scoring             = [[String orchestra]]\n| misc                = Written in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to contaminated blood\n}}\n\n'''''Sanguis Venenatus''''' is an elegy for strings by English composer [[Andrew March]] written in memory of [[haemophiliac]]s (and others) affected by the [[United Kingdom tainted blood scandal|Tainted Blood Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday \u2013 Verity Sharp, Late Junction \u2013 BBC Radio 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06g6456|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanguis Venenatus \u2013 Andrew March & Moravian Philharmonic Strings Song \u2013 BBC Music|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802015204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n3x4nm|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Composers \u2013 Alliance Publications, Inc.|url=http://www.apimusic.org/march-andrew-b.1973.html|website=www.apimusic.org|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenberg |first=Donald |date=March 2013 |title=Sounds of America |url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/34724/page/9|work=Gramophone |location=UK |access-date=2020-04-19|quote=''Slow, aching lines and mild dissonances also inhabit Andrew March\u2032s intensely felt \u2033Sanguis venenatus\u2033.''}}</ref><ref name=\"Todmorden1\">{{cite web|title=Reviews \u2013 Todmorden Orchestra|url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/|website=Todmorden Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item = Sanguis Venenatus |item-url =https://rcm.koha-ptfs.co.uk/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=249942 |type = Audio CD |item-id = |date = 2012 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = NV5895 Navona Records |collection = In Dimensions : works for string orchestra|repository = RCM Library Catalogue|institution = Royal College of Music |location = London |oclc= |accession= |ref=CD11802}}</ref> The elegy was included in a service on 30 March, 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/4247/chronically-sick-disabled-persons-act-service.pdf |title=A service to mark the 40th anniversay of the coming into effect of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 March 2011 |website= |publisher=Westminster Abbey |access-date=2020-04-18 |quote=}}</ref> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the UK legislation&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970). ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was dedicated to the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]], to recognise his long\u2013standing support and advocacy for persons with haemophilia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> \n\n==Composition==\nIn 2009, Andrew March completed a cycle of 10 string quartets based on the characteristics of [[diurnal]] [[birds of prey]]. The fifth piece, entitled ''Elegy for an Unsuspecting [[Red phalarope|Phalarope]]'' was inspired by the image of a huge [[Common buzzard|buzzard]] snatching a small grey [[Wader|wading bird]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> The photograph, which appeared in [[The Times]], was taken by two birdwatchers, Paul Freestone and Tim Twiggs at [[St Gothian Sands]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=de Bruxelles|first=Simon |date=16 January 2009 |title=Horrified twitchers watch as starving buzzard kills rare phalarope |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/horrified-twitchers-watch-as-starving-buzzard-kills-rare-phalarope-53hkjvdddgc |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |date=16 January 2009 |title=Buzzard kills rare visitor to British shores |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/jan/16/wildlife-cornwall |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This image was used by March as a poignant metaphor for the disaster which befell thousands of haemophiliacs through [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood products]] with which they were treated.<ref name=\"Todmorden1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W4gy-7IlUqg YouTube, (''Sanguis Venenatus'')]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n[[Category:Music with dedications]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n\n{{Music-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Adding category \"2009 compositions\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanguis_Venenatus"}
{"title_page": "Brooks Stadium", "text_new": "{{About|the football stadium in South Carolina|the baseball stadium in Kentucky|J. Polk Brooks Stadium}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Brooks Stadium / James C. Benton Field\n| image             = CoastalBrooksStad1.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| caption           = The entrance to Brooks Stadium\n| address           = 540 University Blvd\n| location          = [[Conway, South Carolina]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|33.793013|-79.017652|region:US-SC_type:landmark|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map       = USA South Carolina#USA\n| pushpin_relief    = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in South Carolina##Location in the United States\n| pushpin_label     = Brooks Stadium\n| broke_ground      = July 30, 2002\n| opened            = September 6, 2003\n| renovated         = 2017\n| expanded          = 2010, 2017\u20132018\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Coastal Carolina University]]\n| operator          = Coastal Carolina University\n| surface           = Shaw Sports PowerBlade (teal) (2015\u2013present)<br>Grass (2003\u20132014)\n| construction_cost = $59 Million \n| architect         = McMillan Smith & Partners\n| general_contractor= Hill Construction<ref>{{cite web|title=Coastal Carolina University Stadium|url=http://www.hillcon.com/completed_projects/Sports/Coastal%20Carolina%20%20University%20Stadium.pdf|publisher=Hill Construction|accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n| tenants           = [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (2003\u2013present)\n| seating_capacity  = 21,000 (2019\u2013present)<br> 15,000 (2017\u20132018)<br>9,214 (2012\u20132016)<br>9,112 (2010\u20132011)<br>7,322 (2006\u20132009)<br>6,408 (2003\u20132005)\n|}}\n'''Brooks Stadium''' is a 21,000-seat [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Conway, South Carolina]]. It is home to the [[Coastal Carolina Chanticleers football]] team at [[Coastal Carolina University]] .  The facility opened in 2003 and is named in honor of Coby Garrett Brooks and Boni Belle Brooks, children of [[Robert H. Brooks|Robert ''\"Bob\"'' Brooks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.coastal.edu/news/print.php?id=679|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060922105026/http://www.coastal.edu/news/print.php?id=679|url-status=dead|title=Football stadium at Coastal to be named for Brooks|archivedate=September 22, 2006}}</ref>  Brooks was a [[Loris, South Carolina]] native and was the chairman of [[Hooters|Hooters of America, Inc]]. The stadium is notable for its teal [[artificial turf]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Coastal Carolina going with teal for new artificial turf|url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/01/25/coastal-carolina-going-with-teal-for-new-artificial-turf/|last=McGuire|first=Kevin|work=NBC Sports|date=January 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History and renovation==\nGroundbreaking for Brooks Stadium was held on July 30, 2002. Phase I of the stadium construction contained 6,408 seats, while the foundation and infrastructure of the stadium was designed to support future expansion to 20,000 seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coastal.edu/newsarticles/story.php?id=679 |title=Football stadium at Coastal to be named for Brooks |work=Coastal Carolina University |date=August 11, 2013 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> The stadium was formally dedicated on September 6, 2003, as the Chanticleer football team opened its inaugural game vs. Newberry College in front of a crowd of more than 8,000. On October 7, 2006, the field was named James C. Benton Field to honor the family for a large donation they made to the Coastal athletics program earlier in the year.\n\n===2017\u201319 expansion===\nFollowing the announcement of the university joining the [[Sun Belt Conference]] on September 1, 2015, Brooks Stadium underwent construction to expand the stadium to 20,000 seats. The NCAA requires FBS programs to maintain an average attendance of at least 15,000 over a rolling two-year cycle. The expansion project received approval from the state in November 2015, however construction was not expected to begin until January 2017. [[Coastal Carolina University]] officials set the project price tag at $38 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thestate.com/sports/college/article61244687.html |title=Coastal Carolina committee approves $38M bonds for Brooks Stadium expansion |publisher=Coastal Carolina University |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>  The committee also announced in February 2017 the lead architects for the expansion were [[Heery International|Heery International, Inc.]] [[Architecture|architectural]] firm and Stubbs Muldrow Herin architects.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.coastal.edu/media/administration/facilities/pdf/Brooks%20Stadium%20Additions.pdf |title=Brooks Stadium Additions |publisher=Coastal Carolina University |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref> Groundbreaking for the project took place on March 21, 2017. Construction took place over two phases; the first phase expanded the stadium to the FBS-minimum 15,000 seats by expanding the sidelines and connecting them to the north end zone as well as expanding the press box side upper deck. It was completed in time for Coastal Carolina's season opener against [[UMass Minutemen football|UMass]] on September 2, 2017. Construction of phase II began in January 2018, and further expanded capacity to over 20,000 seats by adding premium seating and an upper deck to the west side.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coastal Has Football Stadium Expansion Groundbreaking Ceremony|url=http://www.goccusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/032117aaa.html|publisher=Coastal Carolina University Athletics|accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref> Phase II was finished in August 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blondin |first1=Alan |title=Expansion of Brooks Stadium is complete. What the new capacity and features mean for CCU |url=https://www.myrtlebeachonline.com/sports/college/sun-belt/coastal-carolina-university/article233328037.html |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=[[Myrtle Beach Sun News]] |date=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:TS sold out picture fw.png.jpg|thumb|Brooks Stadium Expansion]]\n\n==Marrio & Josh Norman Fieldhouse==\nThe $8.5 million fieldhouse opened at Brooks Stadium in June 2010. It was originally named for brothers Mark and Will Adkins (Coastal Carolina '89), who planned to donate $1.5 million to the project. The fieldhouse added 1,600 seats.\n\nOn November 3, 2018, it was announced that [[Josh Norman]] had donated a large amount of money to the athletic department and the Adkins Fieldhouse name changed to Marrio & Josh Norman Fieldhouse.\n\nThe Marrio & Josh Norman Fieldhouse also includes houses:\n* Football offices, meeting rooms, and football locker room\n* {{convert|13000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Strength & conditioning center for all student-athletes\n* Men's and women's cross country and track & field offices\n* Men's and women's soccer offices\n* Men's and women's golf offices\n* Men's tennis office\n* Baseball office\n* Softball office\n* Sasser Athletic Hall of Fame\n\n==Attendance records==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Coastal Carolina Chanticleers|color=white}}\" |Rank\n!style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Coastal Carolina Chanticleers|color=white}}\" |Attendance\n!style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Coastal Carolina Chanticleers|color=white}}\" |Date\n!style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Coastal Carolina Chanticleers|color=white}}\" |Game Result\n|- align=\"center\"\n| '''1''' || 17,249 || December 10, 2019 || Coastal Carolina 21, '''Georgia State 31'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| '''2''' || 15,991 || July 10, 2017 || Coastal Carolina 21, '''Georgia State 27'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| '''3''' || 15,545 || November 11, 2017 || Coastal Carolina 17, '''Troy 42'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| '''4''' || 15,102 || November 30, 2019 || '''Coastal Carolina 24''', Texas State 21\n|- align=\"center\"\n| '''5''