{"title_page": "Randy Bloom", "text_new": "'''Randy Bloom''' (born 1955) <ref name=\"artslant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artslant.com/global/artists/show/241417-randy-bloom|title=ArtSlant - Randy Bloom|publisher=artslant.com|accessdate=2015-09-22}}</ref> is an internationally exhibited [[United States|American]] painter. Bloom has exhibited at the [[Ivan Karp|O.K Harris]], Tower Gallery,  Gershwin Gallery, Cooper Classics Collection and Jack Tilton galleries in [[New York City]], the accostage and Le Muse galleries in [[Japan]], and the Galleria de arte Magick in [[Easton, Pennsylvania]], among others.  Art critic, [[Carter Ratcliff]] in the journal of a \"[[A Gathering of the Tribes (Cultural Organization)|A Gathering of the Tribes]]\" has written in describing the artist's work....\"thoroughly sophisticated and her forms and colors are mutually clarifying. Yet there is more to her art, because of the mode\u2014or the mood\u2014in which she creates it. This artist doesn\u2019t soberly illuminate or clarify so much as animate or even intoxicate, imbuing her pictorial devices with a giddy sense of the parts they play in the big picture\"....<ref name=\"tribes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribes.org/web/2011/10/07/carter-ratcliffs-thoughts-on-randy-bloom/|title=Carter Ratcliff&#039;s Thoughts on Randy Bloom - A Gathering of the Tribes|publisher=tribes.org|accessdate=2015-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Bloom was awarded a BA in Painting & Art History by Franconia College. <ref name=\"artslant\" />\n\nIn August 1985, Randy Bloom was one of five artists included in a show called \"Two Plus Three\" at the [[Tower Gallery]] in New York City. [[Michael Brenson]], in the New York Times, wrote about the exhibition \"Each artist in the show is, of course, abstract. Each has the Formalist commitment to surface. Each is intent upon exploring the medium itself. Of course, they use acrylic, sometimes spreading it out like sand, sometimes caking it on the canvas like mud.\" Commenting on Bloom's work, Brenson wrote \"Mr. Bloom [sic] digs into it, makes it matte and suggests aerial views of landscapes like Jules Olitski. There is an abiding interest in the sculptural possibilities of paint and a pull toward subject matter.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/08/16/arts/chinese-figure-painting-is-on-exhibit-at-the-met.html|title=CHINESE FIGURE PAINTING IS ON EXHIBIT AT THE MET|last=Brenson|first=Michael|date=16 August 1985|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419000359/https://www.nytimes.com/1985/08/16/arts/chinese-figure-painting-is-on-exhibit-at-the-met.html|archive-date=16 April 2020|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Bloom exhibited a total of fifteen paintings at the Cooper Classics Collection in New York City. The art journalist [[Piri Halasz]] (who has long followed the artist's progress) wrote of the exhibition in [[New York Arts Magazine]], \"Bloom's most recent style has been called a combination of minimalism and color-field. While this description has some truth, her minimalism is not minimal enough to destroy her work's variety and individualism, while the richness and delicacy of her colors, and the freedom with which she applies paint makes her pictures worthy descendants of 60s color-field painting by such masters as Frankenthaler and Noland. Each of the eight large paintings in this show are composed of five to eight strips of color, about six feet long and about four inches wide, spaced more or less evenly across a canvas painted in a contrasting color.\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halasz|first=Phil|date=May 2000|title=Bloom: Mini and/or Color|url=|journal=NY Arts Magazine|volume=Volume 6 Number 5|pages=27|via=}}</ref>\n\nFrom October 20 until November 14, 2015 her recent paintings were the subject of a solo exhibition at the Andre Zarre Gallery in the Soho neighborhood in the borough of Manhattan in New York City.<ref>http://www.andrezarre.com/html/featured_artists_solo_exhibitions.html</ref> In writing about this exhibition in [[observer.com|Observer]] , [[Piri Halasz]] states about the works \"They glow like jewels because each has a base layer of charcoal gray paint that also surrounds its image\u2014setting that image off like the black velvet of a jewelry case\"...<ref>http://observer.com/2015/11/artist-randy-bloom-paints-jewel-like-spines-of-pure-color-in-chelsea/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pirihalasz.com/blog/posts/20413 On the Mayor's Doorstep] by [[Piri Halasz]]\n*[http://www.randybloom.com/#home The artist's website]<br />\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, Randy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Randy Bloom''' (born 1955) <ref name=\"artslant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artslant.com/global/artists/show/241417-randy-bloom|title=ArtSlant - Randy Bloom|publisher=artslant.com|accessdate=2015-09-22}}</ref> is an internationally exhibited [[United States|American]] painter. Bloom has exhibited at the [[Ivan Karp|O.K Harris]], Tower Gallery,  Gershwin Gallery, Cooper Classics Collection and Jack Tilton galleries in [[New York City]], the accostage and Le Muse galleries in [[Japan]], and the Galleria de arte Magick in [[Easton, Pennsylvania]], among others.  Art critic, [[Carter Ratcliff]] in the journal of a \"[[A Gathering of the Tribes (Cultural Organization)|A Gathering of the Tribes]]\" has written in describing the artist's work....\"thoroughly sophisticated and her forms and colors are mutually clarifying. Yet there is more to her art, because of the mode\u2014or the mood\u2014in which she creates it. This artist doesn\u2019t soberly illuminate or clarify so much as animate or even intoxicate, imbuing her pictorial devices with a giddy sense of the parts they play in the big picture\"....<ref name=\"tribes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribes.org/web/2011/10/07/carter-ratcliffs-thoughts-on-randy-bloom/|title=Carter Ratcliff&#039;s Thoughts on Randy Bloom - A Gathering of the Tribes|publisher=tribes.org|accessdate=2015-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Bloom was awarded a BA in Painting & Art History by Franconia College. <ref name=\"artslant\" />\n\nIn August 1985, Randy Bloom was one of five artists included in a show called \"Two Plus Three\" at the [[Tower Gallery]] in New York City. [[Michael Brenson]], in the New York Times, wrote about the exhibition \"Each artist in the show is, of course, abstract. Each has the Formalist commitment to surface. Each is intent upon exploring the medium itself. Of course, they use acrylic, sometimes spreading it out like sand, sometimes caking it on the canvas like mud.\" Commenting on Bloom's work, Brenson wrote \"Mr. Bloom [sic] digs into it, makes it matte and suggests aerial views of landscapes like Jules Olitski. There is an abiding interest in the sculptural possibilities of paint and a pull toward subject matter.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/08/16/arts/chinese-figure-painting-is-on-exhibit-at-the-met.html|title=CHINESE FIGURE PAINTING IS ON EXHIBIT AT THE MET|last=Brenson|first=Michael|date=16 August 1985|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Bloom exhibited a total of fifteen paintings at the Cooper Classics Collection in New York City. The art journalist [[Piri Halasz]] (who has long followed the artist's progress) wrote of the exhibition in [[New York Arts Magazine]], \"Bloom's most recent style has been called a combination of minimalism and color-field. While this description has some truth, her minimalism is not minimal enough to destroy her work's variety and individualism, while the richness and delicacy of her colors, and the freedom with which she applies paint makes her pictures worthy descendants of 60s color-field painting by such masters as Frankenthaler and Noland. Each of the eight large paintings in this show are composed of five to eight strips of color, about six feet long and about four inches wide, spaced more or less evenly across a canvas painted in a contrasting color.\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halasz|first=Phil|date=May 2000|title=Bloom: Mini and/or Color|url=|journal=NY Arts Magazine|volume=Volume 6 Number 5|pages=27|via=}}</ref>\n\nFrom October 20 until November 14, 2015 her recent paintings were the subject of a solo exhibition at the Andre Zarre Gallery in the Soho neighborhood in the borough of Manhattan in New York City.<ref>http://www.andrezarre.com/html/featured_artists_solo_exhibitions.html</ref> In writing about this exhibition in [[observer.com|Observer]] , [[Piri Halasz]] states about the works \"They glow like jewels because each has a base layer of charcoal gray paint that also surrounds its image\u2014setting that image off like the black velvet of a jewelry case\"...<ref>http://observer.com/2015/11/artist-randy-bloom-paints-jewel-like-spines-of-pure-color-in-chelsea/</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pirihalasz.com/blog/posts/20413 On the Mayor's Doorstep] by [[Piri Halasz]]\n*[http://www.randybloom.com/#home The artist's website]<br />\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, Randy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MarylandGeoffrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "Archived the cite just in case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randy_Bloom"}
{"title_page": "Graham Stilwell", "text_new": "{{update section|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name = Graham Stilwell\n|fullname = Graham Rodney Stilwell\n|image = \n|country = {{GBR}}\n|residence =\n|birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1945|11|15}}\n|birth_place = [[Denham, Buckinghamshire]], England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|01|31|1945|11|15}}\n|height = 5 ft 8 in\n|turnedpro = 1968<small> (amateur tour from 1963)\n|retired = 1975\n|plays = Right-handed (one-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney = \n|singlesrecord =\n|singlestitles =\n|highestsinglesranking =\n|AustralianOpenresult = 3R ([[1964 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|1964]], [[1967 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|1967]])\n|FrenchOpenresult = 3R ([[1971 French Open - Men's Singles|1971]])\n|Wimbledonresult = 4R ([[1975 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1975]])\n|USOpenresult = 4R ([[1966 U.S. National Championships - Men's Singles|1966]])\n|doublesrecord = 93\u2013125<small> (Open Era)\n|doublestitles = 3\n|highestdoublesranking =\n|grandslamsdoublesresults    =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = QF ([[1967 Australian Championships#Men's Doubles|1967]], [[1968 Australian Championships#Men's Doubles|1968]])\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult     =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult      = SF ([[1966 Wimbledon Championships#Men's Doubles|1966]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult         = F ([[1964 U.S. National Championships#Men's doubles|1964]])\n|Team = yes\n|DavisCupresult = F ([[1969 Davis Cup|1969]])\n}}\n\n'''Graham Stilwell''' (15 November 1945 \u2013 31 January 2019)<ref name=\"atp_obit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/graham-stilwell-2019-obituary|title=Graham Stilwell: 1945-2019 |date=4 February 2019| author=James Buddell |publisher = Association of Tennis Professionals (ATP)}}</ref> was a professional [[tennis]] player from the United Kingdom. He was born in [[Denham, Buckinghamshire]], England.\n\nStilwell enjoyed most of his tennis success while playing doubles.  During his career he won 3 doubles titles, 2 of which were in the Open Era.\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nStilwell had three children (Tiffany, Alex and Lara) in his first marriage to Robin Lockard. His second marriage to Jill Jacobs resulted in two children (Sam and Romy).<ref name=\"times_obit\">{{cite web |title=Graham Stilwell obituary |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/register/graham-stilwell-obituary-hhh8p0cwc |publisher=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe died of a [[Neuromuscular disease|neuro-muscular disorder]] on 31 January 2019.\n\n==Career finals ==\n\n===Doubles (2 titles, 4 runner-ups)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:55px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:25px\"|No.\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:140px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| 1.\n| 1969\n| [[ATP Stockholm|Stockholm, Sweden]]\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|ESP|1945}} [[Andr\u00e9s Gimeno]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Roy Emerson]] <br> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rod Laver]]\n| 4\u20136, 2\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| 2.\n| 1973\n| [[ATP Copenhagen|Copenhagen WCT, Denmark]]\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Mark Cox (tennis)|Mark Cox]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tom Gorman (tennis)|Tom Gorman]] <br> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Erik van Dillen]]\n| 4\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| 1.\n| 1973\n| [[Cologne, Germany|Cologne WCT, Germany]]\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Mark Cox (tennis)|Mark Cox]]\n| {{flagicon|NED}} [[Tom Okker]] <br> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marty Riessen]]\n| 7\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| 2.\n| 1973\n| [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus, U.S.]]\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Gerald Battrick]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Colin Dibley]] <br> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Charlie Pasarell]]\n| 6\u20134, 7\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"b